"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421155","Home Office","false","2015-10-20","<p>Under the UK-US Treaty there is no practical difference in the treatment of UK and US nationals, or indeed the nationals of any other country. This was also the conclusion of the independent Review of the UK’s Extradition Arrangements which the Home Secretary asked Sir Scott Baker to conduct, which stated “We have concluded that the United States/United Kingdom Treaty does not operate in an unbalanced manner” and that “there is no practical difference between the information submitted to and from the United States”. Changes were made to the operation of the Treaty in the last Parliament, such as the introduction of the 'forum bar' under the Anti-Social Behaviour, Crime and Policing Act 2014. The Government believes that the Treaty is operating fairly.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-10-20T16:26:37.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421155/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421155/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421155/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-13","Extradition: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans she has to amend the US-UK extradition treaty to make the legal requirements for extradition the same for US and UK citizens.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421156","Department for International Development","false","2015-10-20","<p>The UK has been at the forefront of the response to the crisis in Syria and the region and has pledged over £1.1 billion to date, our largest ever response to a single humanitarian crisis. We have allocated £559 million to support refugees in the region and £561 million to support those in need inside Syria.Our support has reached hundreds of thousands of people in Syria, Jordan, Lebanon, Turkey, Iraq and Egypt. By the end of June 2015, our support in Syria and the region had delivered almost 20 million food rations, provided over 2.5 million medical consultations and resulted in over 7.2 million instances when people benefited from sanitation and hygiene activities.</p><br /><p>The UK prioritises its assistance according to where needs are greatest, and works with trusted humanitarian organisations to assist the most vulnerable populations in hard-to-reach areas.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-10-20T16:05:34.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421156/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421156/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421156/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-10-13","Syria: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how UK aid has been used to assist refugees near the Syrian border to date; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421157","Department for International Development","false","2015-10-19","<p>The UN World Food Programme has warned that Yemen is “one step away from famine”. Over 12 million people – almost half of the population - are struggling to find enough food to eat. Of those, 6 million people are facing severe food shortages. In Hodeidah city alone, UNICEF have warned that 96,000 children are starving and at risk of dying. The ongoing conflict continues to affect imports of commercial and humanitarian supplies – especially essential fuel, food and medicines - into Yemen and the distribution of food to those who need it most.</p><br /><p>The UK is one of the largest donors to the crisis in Yemen and has announced £75 million to respond to the humanitarian crisis in Yemen, focused on the most urgent life-saving needs. UK aid is providing vital medical supplies, water, food and emergency shelter, as well as supporting UN work to co-ordinate the international humanitarian response.</p><br /><p>Despite severe food shortages, there has not yet been a significant movement of people from Yemen to neighbouring countries in the Middle East and North Africa. Djibouti and Somalia have received the highest number of refugees since the escalation of the conflict in Yemen in March 2015.To improve the living conditions of migrants and refugees from Yemen in Djibouti, the UK is supporting the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees and the International Organisation for Migration with in-kind assistance consisting of shelter kits, water containers, family kitchen sets, blankets, hygiene kits and solar lanterns. The UK is also providing a package of food, health and shelter assistance to refugees from Yemen in Somalia.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-10-19T16:12:50.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421157/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421157/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421157/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-10-13","Middle East and North Africa: Famine","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the risk of famine in Yemen; and what assessment she has made of the possible humanitarian implications of famine in the Middle East and North Africa.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","11645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421158","Department for International Development","false","2015-10-19","<p>The conflict in Yemen has resulted in severe restrictions on imports of humanitarian and commercial supplies into the country, including essential fuel, food and medicines. According to the UN, since April, Yemen has received 2.1 million metric tonnes of food (90% through commercial imports and 10% through humanitarian aid) but only 25% of its estimated fuel needs.</p><br /><p>The UK continues to call on all parties to facilitate unimpeded and immediate humanitarian access to all people in need in Yemen, and to lift any restrictions on commercial and humanitarian shipping.</p><br /><p>The UK is one of the largest donors to the crisis in Yemen and has announced £75 million to respond to the humanitarian crisis in Yemen, focused on the most urgent life-saving needs. UK aid is providing vital medical supplies, water, food and emergency shelter, as well as supporting UN work to co-ordinate the international humanitarian response.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-10-19T16:16:38.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421158/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421158/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421158/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-10-13","Yemen: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the effect of the ongoing de facto blockade of Yemen by the government of Yemen and the Saudi-led coalition on (a) aid and (b) commercial supplies to that country.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","11646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421159","Department for International Development","false","2015-10-19","<p>The UK continues to call on all parties to facilitate rapid, safe and unhindered access to all people in need in Yemen, and to lift any restrictions on commercial and humanitarian shipping.</p><br /><p>The UK is one of the largest donors to the crisis in Yemen and has announced £75 million to respond to the humanitarian crisis in Yemen, focused on the most urgent life-saving needs. UK aid is providing vital medical supplies, water, food and emergency shelter, as well as supporting UN work to co-ordinate the international humanitarian response.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-10-19T16:09:10.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421159/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421159/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421159/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-10-13","Yemen: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will take steps to ensure that all parties involved in the conflict in Yemen allow unimpeded humanitarian access (a) into and (b) within the country to reach people in need.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","11647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421160","Department for International Development","false","2015-10-19","<p>DFID is focussing its bilateral programme on reducing new HIV infection rates in southern Africa, the region hardest-hit by the epidemic. Our efforts are focused on the integration of HIV prevention and treatment services within sexual and reproductive health programmes. A particular emphasis is on the needs of women and girls and those populations most at risk.</p><br /><p>DFID is increasingly working through multilateral organisations, which can work in many more countries than the UK can reach on its own and at a much larger scale. That is why the UK made a commitment of up to a £1 billion to the Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria (GFATM) for the 2014–16 replenishment.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-10-19T15:15:28.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421160/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421160/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421160/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-10-13","Sub-Saharan Africa: HIV Infection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to reduce the number of new HIV infections in sub-Saharan Africa.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11689"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421161","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-10-20","<p>A report is being prepared for publication, subject to standard quality assurance checks.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-10-20T14:49:54.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421161/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421161/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421161/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-10-13","Witnesses: Video Recordings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when he plans to complete the evaluation of the pilots of section 28 of the Youth Justice and Criminal Evidence Act 1999; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ann Coffey","Stockport","Ann Coffey","11778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421163","Leader of the House","false","2015-10-16","<p>On Thursday 15 October 2015 I published the Government's updated proposals for English votes for English laws. I had many discussions before publishing these updated proposals, including with Ministerial Colleagues and officials, and I have also listened to the Procedure Committee. The House will have the opportunity to debate the issue on Thursday 22 October 2015.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2015-10-16T09:56:43.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421163/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421163/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421163/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2015-10-13","English Votes for English Laws","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, what discussions he has had with Ministers or officials of HM Treasury on the effect of Government proposals for English votes for English laws on the future of the block grant for Scotland.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","11757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421164","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-10-19","<p>It is essential that the cross-party talks deliver a way to implement the Stormont House Agreement and also a means to address the continuing impact of paramilitary organisations.</p><p>The Northern Ireland parties are engaging intensively on these issues but time is short and a resolution is needed urgently.</p><br />","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2015-10-19T12:08:12.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421164/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421164/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421164/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-10-13","Northern Ireland Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what progress she has made in resolving the political situation in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11700"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421165","Prime Minister","false","2015-10-21","<p>The Government will always act in defence of the UK and in accordance with our legal obligations.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2015-10-21T14:34:27.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421165/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421165/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421165/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2015-10-13","Capital Punishment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, under which conditions he can order the killing of a UK citizen resident abroad.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","11643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421166","Home Office","false","2015-11-13","<p>Scaling up the system in a way that protects the interests of all concerned, including local communities, will take a little bit of time. It will take several months to reach full capacity. However, on 19 October, I set out our intention to welcome 1,000 Syrian refugees (adults and children) before Christmas. This is the ambition that the Home Office are working towards and we will report on it after Christmas.</p><p>We are not expecting the refugees arriving in the first months of the scheme to include unaccompanied children.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2015-11-13T14:54:42.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421166/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421166/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421166/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-13","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will ensure that at least 1,000 Syrian children are brought to settle in the UK before Christmas 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","11546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421167","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office is an integral part of the Cabinet Office.</p><p>The Cabinet Office adheres to the Government Buying Standards for Food and Catering Services which are mandatory for central Government and its executive agencies, ALBs, NDPBs etc. This is supported in the DEFRA Business Plan to drive sustainable food procurement by the Government and the public sector.</p><p>The Government Buying Standards on Food and Catering can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/418072/gbs-food-catering-march2015.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/418072/gbs-food-catering-march2015.pdf</a></p><p>Milk provided for official purposes in the Cabinet Office is supplied by the department’s facilities management provider. Expenditure on milk specifically is not identified separately on the department’s financial systems and, as a result, information on such expenditure is not held centrally.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-10-16T13:07:01.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421167/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421167/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421167/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-13","Prime Minister: Milk","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much (a) fair price milk and (b) non-fair price milk was purchased for use in 10 Downing Street in August 2015; and what plans he has to ensure that only fair price milk is used at 10 Downing Street in future.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","11728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421168","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-16","<p>The HS2 Plus Report by Sir David Higgins, which was published in March 2014, highlighted a number of issues with HS2-HS1 link proposed in the Phase One hybrid Bill. In response to the HS2 Plus report, the Secretary of State decided to remove the HS1-HS2 link from the Phase One Hybrid Bill as it required too many compromises in terms of impacts on freight, passengers and the community in Camden.</p><p>The Secretary of State has therefore asked HS2 Ltd to consider how to improve connections to the continent. This connectivity study, which is nearing completion, will explore options to improve connections to the continent. We expect the study to be completed by the end of this year.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-10-16T10:03:09.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421168/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421168/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421168/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Railways: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to his Department's letter of 11 April 2014 to the Chief Executive of HS2 Ltd, when he plans to publish the advice by HS2 Ltd and Network Rail on improving connections to European rail networks referred to in that letter.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","11753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421169","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-16","<p>The information requested is not available in this form. However, details of the annual amounts paid to individual bus operators in England, and the local authority area in which they are based, can be found at the following links for 2014/15, 2013/14 and 2012/13:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/bus-service-operators-grant-payments-to-english-operators-up-to-31-march-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/bus-service-operators-grant-payments-to-english-operators-up-to-31-march-2015</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/bus-service-operators-grant-payments-to-english-operators-up-to-31-march-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/bus-service-operators-grant-payments-to-english-operators-up-to-31-march-2014</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/bus-service-operators-grant-payments-to-english-operators-up-to-31-march-2013" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/bus-service-operators-grant-payments-to-english-operators-up-to-31-march-2013</a></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-10-16T09:50:29.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421169/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421169/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421169/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Bus Service Operators Grant","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what his Department's average spend on Bus Service Operators Grant was per capita in each English region in each year from 2010-11 to 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","11751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421170","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-16","<p>The United Kingdom has ratified and transposed into domestic law the International Labour Organization’s Maritime Labour Convention, 2006 (MLC) which includes provisions on the payment of wages.</p><p>For UK registered ships other than those which are subject to the MLC, section 30 of the Merchant Shipping Act 1995 makes provision for the late payment of wages, and interest is payable on late sums under specified circumstances.</p><p>Enforcement is carried out by Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA) surveyors (and any surveyors nominated by the MCA to carry out surveys and inspections) on UK registered ships in routine surveys and inspections, and, where applicable, on non-UK registered ships during port State Control inspections.</p><p>We are not aware of any incidents of non-payment of wages on board any UK registered vessels.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-10-16T09:32:12.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421170/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421170/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421170/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Shipping: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to reduce the incidences of non-payment of wages to seafarers working in (a) UK and (b) Europe.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","11747"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421171","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-16","<p>No estimate has been made of unpaid wages owed to seafarers working on vessels registered in the UK or for shipping companies operating out of the UK in (a) 2013 and (b) 2014.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-10-16T09:41:42.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421171/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421171/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421171/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Shipping: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the total in unpaid wages owed to seafarers working in the UK shipping industry in (a) 2013 and (b) 2014.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","11748"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421172","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-16","<p>At the start of April 2015, there were 226 Temporary Speed Restrictions (TSR) on Network Rail infrastructure. As of 9th October (end of week 3, Period 7) there were 331 TSRs on the network.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-16T13:09:48.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421172/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421172/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421172/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Railways: Speed Limits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many temporary speed restrictions were in place on Network Rail infrastructure on (a) 1 April and (b) the most recent date for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","11755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421173","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA) carry out Port State Control inspections on board foreign vessels in UK waters. The Port State Control regime has a requirement of no more favourable treatment to other vessels many of which are registered in these so called “open registers”.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-10-16T09:15:24.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421173/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421173/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421173/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Shipping: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will raise with (a) his ministerial colleagues and (b) the International Labour Organisation the extent of non-compliance amongst open registers with the minimum standards for seafarers' rights established in the Maritime Labour Convention 2006.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","11746"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421174","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA) is not aware of the findings of the International Transport Workers Federation's Maritime Labour Convention compliance inspections on international shipping in 2014. However, you may wish to note that the MCA works very closely with The International Transport Workers Federation (ITF). When ITF inspectors have concerns on board, they notify the MCA who subsequently carry out a review of the issues and carry out a Port State Control inspection, if deemed necessary. This would either result in deficiencies being raised or the ship being detained until satisfactory corrective actions are initiated in response to the deficiencies raised.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-10-16T09:11:00.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421174/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421174/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421174/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Shipping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the findings of the International Transport Workers Federation's Maritime Labour Convention compliance inspections on international shipping in 2014.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","11745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421175","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-16","<p>Unpausing electrification of the Midland Mainline and the North TransPennine route has not caused the Department to incur any immediate additional costs.</p><p>With regard to Network Rail’s costs, Midland Mainline electrification was in the delivery phase at the time of pause and Network Rail are still working to understand the costs associated with the decision to unpause. The North TransPennine route is still in development and costs were not affected by the decision to recommence electrification.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-16T12:30:02.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421175/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421175/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421175/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Railways: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the estimated cost is to (a) his Department and (b) Network Rail of unpausing electrification of the Midland Main Line and the North TransPennine route.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","11754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421176","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-16","<p>EY, previously known as Ernst &amp; Young, was engaged in developing the work referred to in Question 9602, and was paid £230k (excluding VAT) in respect of that work.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-16T12:26:40.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421176/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421176/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421176/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Network Rail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2015 to Question 9602, which external organisations received payments from his Department in connection with developing the policies referred to in that Answer; and what amount was paid to each such organisation.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","11759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421177","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-21","<p>The Department provides support for seafarer training through the Support for Maritime Training (SMarT) scheme, the budget for which was increased by 25% to £15million in September 2013. A company or group which elects for the Tonnage Tax is required, each year, to recruit one new officer trainee for every fifteen officer posts in its fleet. We have additionally introduced an option, from 1 October 2015, which allows companies or groups in Tonnage Tax to recruit and train three Able Seafarer ratings each year in place of one trainee officer.</p><br /><p>The industry and the Government are working together to encourage and support the next generation of seafarers and are developing a range of apprenticeships for maritime occupations at sea and ashore. We support the work of the Merchant Navy Training Board and SeaVision in promoting maritime careers, and we collaborated with Maritime UK in the production of an “Open for Maritime Skills” pamphlet. However, the recruitment and training of merchant seafarers is principally a matter for the shipping industry itself.</p><br /><p>The Maritime Growth Study, chaired by Lord Mountevans, was published on 7 September 2015 and contained a number of recommendations for government and industry on skills, including to help maintain the UK’s future supply of seafarers. The Government will formally respond to the Study by the end of the year.</p><br />","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-10-21T13:57:25.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421177/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421177/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421177/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Shipping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to increase the supply of UK (a) domiciled and (b) trained seafarers to the shipping industry.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","11534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421178","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-19","<p>The Shipping and Ports Strategic Partnership Plans are active and remain helpful tools for government and industry to agree joint priorities and actions and to provide a cohesive platform for future strategic development. The Maritime Business Services Strategic Partnership Plan is agreed with Industry and is due to be published imminently.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-10-19T11:32:44.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421178/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421178/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421178/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Shipping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the current status is of the Shipping Strategic Plans for the (a) shipping, (b) ports and (c) business services sectors of the UK maritime industry; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","11537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421179","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-21","<p>The Government engages regularly with representative bodies responsible for maritime training. These training representatives, including some maritime training colleges, contributed to the evidence gathering process that informed the Maritime Growth Study. As several recommendations from the Study focus on maritime training provision we intend to keep relevant training bodies fully informed and involved as we begin to take these forward.</p><br />","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-10-21T13:53:24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421179/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421179/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421179/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Shipping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what meetings he has planned over the next six months with maritime training colleges to discuss the recommendations of the Maritime Growth Study.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","11533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421180","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-16","<p>On 23 March 2015, a senior Department for Transport (DfT) committee commissioned Network Rail, the Office of Rail and Road, and DfT officials to jointly assess the whole enhancements portfolio and provide a more robust estimate of costs. Senior officials from all three organisations met on 26 March 2015 to discuss how we could work together to undertake this piece of work.</p><p>The Secretary of State did not specifically instruct this work nor was he part of these two meetings.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-16T09:59:40.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421180/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421180/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421180/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Railways: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether officials in his Department were acting on his authority when they instructed Network Rail and the Office of Rail and Road on 26 March 2015 on how the further assessment of Control Period 5's cost estimates was to be carried out.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","11601"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421181","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-21","<p>The Government is currently considering the very detailed analysis contained in the Airports Commission’s final report.</p><br /><p>Any decision regarding future airport capacity will take into account the Government’s overall plan to improve air quality and its commitment to comply with EU air quality standards.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-10-21T12:30:24.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421181/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421181/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421181/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Pippins School","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the National Atmospheric Emission Inventory results for the nitrogen dioxide levels at Pippins Primary School, Colnbrook, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on the health of pupils and staff at that school of the proposals by the Davies Commission to expand Heathrow Airport.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","11586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421182","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-21","<p>Network Rail has 68 positions based across its eight routes with various responsibilities for managing commercial and regulated relationships with industry customers (the various operators). These roles are important in ensuring effective partnerships between Network Rail and the wider industry in order to meet the needs of passengers.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-21T12:36:10.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421182/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421182/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421182/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Network Rail: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many staff are employed by Network Rail to deal with contractual interface issues.","true","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","11669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421183","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-16","<p><strong></strong></p><p>In the UK, the Vehicle Certification Agency conducts tests on vehicles and components to ensure they meet the minimum standards required by European and UN-ECE legislation.</p><p>Emissions tests are carried out to determine that the level of pollutants emitted from a vehicle is below the required limits. The test is a laboratory based test under controlled conditions in order to achieve repeatable results.</p><p>The Department for Transport recognises the current test cycle for emissions is outdated and no longer represents normal driving patterns. Discussions have taken place over recent years to replace this with an updated more relevant laboratory test. The Department anticipates this will be implemented from 2017. In addition, a new real world driving emissions test is being implemented to ensure emissions in normal driving comply with the legal obligation. These new tests will remove the ability of car manufacturers to falsify test results.</p><p>All new vehicles are tested in accordance with EU law to ensure that they meet the legislated requirements for emissions. There is no evidence that these emissions tests have been falsified in the UK.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-10-16T12:47:47.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421183/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421183/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421183/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Motor Vehicles: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department plans to take to ensure that automotive manufacturers have not falsified emissions data in the same manner as Volkswagen has done.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421184","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-21","<p>£35m was spent repairing the most damaged section of the track and sea wall and associated works during the initial 56-day work period at Dawlish. Work to raise the walkway is additional and has an anticipated final cost of £15.3m. Funding came in two phases: Phase 1 emergency work was funded primarily from insurance with the Network Rail structures renewals budget paying the excess of £2m. Phase 2 (raising the walkway) will be funded through Network Rail’s Control Period 5 (2019-24) structure renewals budget.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-21T12:47:14.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421184/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421184/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421184/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Railways: Dawlish","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much it cost to reconstruct the railway at Dawlish; and from which budget that cost was met.","true","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","11670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421185","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-21","<p>I regularly meet with airlines to discuss a range of issues. The administration charges related to the refund of Air Passenger Duty has been raised previously. Many airlines do offer a refund of flight taxes including Air Passenger Duty, although some charge an administration fee for processing the refund.</p><br />","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-10-21T12:14:33.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421185/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421185/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421185/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Air Passenger Duty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what meetings he has had with airlines in which the administration charges for customers claiming back Air Passenger Duty were discussed; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","11607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421186","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-21","<p>The Government regularly meets with unions on maritime matters. They were fully engaged in the Maritime Growth Study, contributing through interview, workshops and written submissions to the evidence gathering process that informed the Study. Representatives of the unions also attended the publication event for the Study report on 7 September. We will continue to engage with unions and keep them fully informed and involved as we take forward any recommendations.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-10-21T14:03:27.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421186/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421186/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421186/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Shipping: Trade Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what meetings he has planned over the next six months with maritime trades unions on the recommendations of his Department's Maritime Growth Study published in September 2015.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","11606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421187","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-21","<p>Network Rail have no lawyers employed to deal with this topic, they may become involved in larger and more contentious delay attribution disputes but time commitment will vary significantly.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-21T13:42:55.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421187/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421187/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421187/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Network Rail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many lawyers are employed by Network Rail to work on delay attribution issues with the staff of train operating companies.","true","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","11676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421188","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-21","<p>167 staff at Network Rail have responsibilities in train delay attribution, representing around 0.5% of Network Rail’s total staff. This number of staff dealing with train delay attribution has remained fairly constant over recent years. Network Rail is a company of c. 35,000 staff operating a network that transports 1.66bn passengers a year, and being able to accurately measure how its work impacts on train performance is essential to maintaining and improving a high standard of service.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-21T13:04:50.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421188/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421188/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421188/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Network Rail: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many staff are employed by Network Rail to deal with delay attribution issues with train operating staff.","true","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","11674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421189","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-21","<p>Network Rail has 26 lawyers in the company. None are employed full time to deal specifically with these types of contractual interface issues. Those in the Routes Legal Team (c 12 lawyers) will spend a percentage of their time on these issues and to a lesser extent those in the Corporate Legal Team (c 3 lawyers).Input from the team will vary considerably depending on the nature and size of the issue that has arisen.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-21T13:37:13.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421189/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421189/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421189/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Network Rail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many lawyers are employed by Network Rail to deal with contractual interface issues.","true","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","11675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421190","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-21","<p>Since Network Rail’s reclassification to the public sector in 2014, the Department has engaged EY (previously known as Ernst &amp; Young) to support the development of policy on the future of rail infrastructure management. The final cost of this work was £750k.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-21T13:00:16.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421190/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421190/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421190/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Network Rail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what consultants have been used to advise the Government on the future structure of Network Rail; and what the cost to the public purse has been of engaging such consultants.","true","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","11673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421191","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-21","<p>The Maritime Growth Study was commissioned by Government, but led on an entirely voluntary basis by an industry chair, Lord Mountevans, who was supported by a secretariat of five full-time officials from my Department. The Study was officially launched in November 2014 and published in September 2015. The total cost of the Study was approximately £390K, the majority of these costs being internal staffing costs for the secretariat. Other officials and analysts contributed their expertise as and when required <em>on a business as usual basis</em>.</p><br /><p>The Government will respond formally to the report by the end of 2015, but is taking immediate action in response to specific recommendations. This includes the establishment of a Ministerial Working Group for Maritime Growth and taking steps to support the improved operation of the Maritime &amp; Coastguard Agency (MCA) such as appointing a commercial director to lead the UK Ship Register separately from the Agency’s regulatory functions and a business case exploring the costs and benefits of options for more significant reform of the MCA.</p><br /> <br />","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-10-21T14:11:18.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421191/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421191/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421191/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-13","Shipping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the total cost was of his Department's Maritime Growth Study, published in September 2015; how many hours staff in his Department worked on that study; and when he plans to respond to its recommendations.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","11630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421192","Women and Equalities","false","2015-10-20","<p>The gender pay gap has fallen to its lowest ever level, but any gap is unacceptable. The Prime Minister has pledged to eliminate this gap in a generation. Our recent consultation will inform new regulations that will deliver our manifesto commitment to require large companies to publish details of their gender pay gap. We will also tackle the causes by encouraging girls to consider a wide range of careers and ensuring that workplaces are fit for the 21<sup>st</sup> century.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2015-10-20T09:07:10.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421192/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421192/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421192/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2015-10-13","Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what steps the Government is taking to reduce the gender pay gap.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","11633"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421193","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-21","<p>The department has made no specific assessment of the effectiveness of anonymising job applications in tackling discrimination in the jobs market.</p><p>Early discussions are currently taking place between DWP and large employers through employer roundtables about the scope for reforming recruitment policy through anonymised applications.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-10-21T15:57:50.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421193/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421193/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421193/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-13","Recruitment: Discrimination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of anonymising job applications in tackling discrimination in the jobs market.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","11627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421194","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-19","<p>The Department will be ensure that impartial advice is provided to all claimants, including pensioners, on taking out a loan. This will ensure that all claimants are able to make informed decisions about taking a SMI loan.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-10-19T13:03:54.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421194/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421194/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421194/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-13","Support for Mortgage Interest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what specific guidance and advice his Department will be issuing to pensioners on the change in the Support for Mortgage Interest scheme from a benefit to an interest-bearing loan.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","11764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421195","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-22","<p>The priority for younger workers is to gain skills and experience and to secure work. This is already reflected in the National Minimum Wage rate structure, where the youth rate is currently £1.40 lower than the adult rate. This reflects that wages tend to increase through the early 20s, as workers gain more experience. Youth unemployment is higher compared to those over 25.</p><p>The wages of younger workers will continue to be underpinned by the National Minimum Wage as recommended by the Low Pay Commission at the highest possible level without affecting employment.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-10-22T14:12:31.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421195/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421195/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421195/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-13","Young People: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department is taking to improve rates of pay for people aged under 25.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","11768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421196","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-19","<p>Housing Benefit expenditure information is available in our Benefit Expenditure tables which can be found at: <br><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/benefit-expenditure-and-caseload-tables-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/benefit-expenditure-and-caseload-tables-2015</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-10-19T12:58:37.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421196/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421196/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421196/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-13","Housing Benefit: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much was spent on housing benefit between 2010 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","11765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421197","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-19","All SMI claimants, including pensioners, will continue to receive the same level of support as now towards their mortgage interest when it becomes a loan. As a result no claimants, including pensioners, will receive less in SMI payments than they would now. ","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-10-19T12:50:27.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421197/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421197/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421197/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-13","Support for Mortgage Interest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many pensioners will lose money as a result of changing the Support for Mortgage Interest scheme from a benefit to an interest-bearing loan; and what the average annual loss will be for such pensioners.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","11761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421198","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) takes seriously any declarations of intention to attempt suicide or self harm that are made by its customers. There is a clear, detailed action plan that staff must follow if a customer declares an intention to kill or harm themselves. DWP also provides guidance to help its staff deal with these incidents. The policy, procedures and guidance are reviewed regularly to ensure that they continue to meet their objectives and to identify areas for improvement.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-10-16T13:07:53.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421198/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421198/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421198/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-13","Social Security Benefits: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what processes and procedures are in place when benefit claimants report having suicidal thoughts.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","11775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421199","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-20","<p>A reliable estimate is not available. Consistent data on SMI claims has only been collected since 1996 and durations of claims starting before then cannot be calculated.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-10-20T13:11:25.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421199/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421199/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421199/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-13","Support for Mortgage Interest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average length of time is that pensioners currently in receipt of the Support for Mortgage Interest scheme have been claiming that benefit.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","11762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421200","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-19","<p>The interest rate charged on the loans will be tied to the Office for Budget Responsibility’s (OBR) forecast for gilts rates, so that the interest reflects the government cost of borrowing.</p><p>The rate will be updated every 6 months and is forecast to be 2.9% in 2018/19. (OBR forecast Budget 2015).</p><p>The fees charged will reflect the forecast average cost of administering the loans scheme. Until a provider has been appointed it is not possible to state what those fees might be.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-10-19T14:47:47.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421200/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421200/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421200/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-13","Support for Mortgage Interest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate his Department has made of the level of administration fees and interest charges to pensioners under the Support for Mortgage Interest loan scheme.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","11763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421201","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-15","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 2 July 2015 to Question<a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-06-24/3938/" target="_blank">3938</a></p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-10-15T15:13:45.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421201/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421201/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421201/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-13","Social Security Benefits: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he will respond to the Work and Pensions Committee Report on Benefit sanctions beyond the Oakley review, Fifth Report of Session 2014-15, HC 814.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","11766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421202","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-22","<p>Figures from Action Fraud, the UK’s national reporting centre for fraud and internet crime, show that there were 261 crime reports from 1<sup>st</sup> April to 30<sup>th</sup> August 2015 classified as Pension Liberation Fraud. The average number of reports per month has declined so far this financial year, with an average of 52 reports per month compared to an average of 79 crime reports for financial year 2014/2015.</p><br /><p>However, it is too early to tell what impact the freedoms have had on prevalence of fraud. These figures relate to “reported fraud” only – figures taking account of “actual fraud” will take much longer to flow through.</p><br /><p>Monitoring the market for scams and misselling is the responsibility of the regulators, the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) and the Pensions Regulator. The FCA, in line with its remit to protect consumers and ensure markets function in consumers’ interests, has specifically committed to monitoring developments in the retirement income market closely and to take action where consumers are coming to harm or where the market is not operating competitively. The Government remains in close contact with the regulators, and other organisations such as industry trade bodies, on these issues.</p><br /><p>Pension Wise, the Government’s free and impartial guidance service, also helps individuals understand how to spot and avoid scams. Where its users are at risk or have been scammed, they are referred to the appropriate organisations, such as Action Fraud.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-10-22T14:51:31.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421202/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421202/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421202/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","Pensions: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of changes in the level of scam activity associated with pensions following the introduction of pensions freedoms.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","11771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421203","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-22","<p>Provision of temporary accommodation ensures that homeless households in priority need are not left without a roof over their heads.</p><p>We have provided more than £500 million since 2010 to support local authorities and the voluntary and community sector to tackle and prevent homelessness. This has helped prevent homelessness for 935,000 households.</p><p>Households leaving temporary accommodation now spend, on average, 7 months less in temporary accommodation than they did in 2010.</p><p>The numbers of households in temporary accommodation remain well below their peak, when they hit 101,000 in 2004.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-10-22T15:16:37.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421203/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421203/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421203/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-13","Temporary Accommodation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the reasons for the increase in the number of people relying on temporary accommodation since 2010.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","11767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421204","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-20","<p>The information requested is not available.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-10-20T12:33:53.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421204/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421204/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421204/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-13","Pensioners: Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of pensioners who will not be exempt from the size criteria of universal credit.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","11772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421205","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-20","<p>We have greatly reduced sickness absence in DWP from an average of 11.1 days per employee eight years ago to just 6.4 days per employee now. This is below the figure for the public sector of 7.9 days on average per employee, which was independently reported by the Chartered Institute for Personnel and Development in its latest sickness absence report.</p><br /><p>The number of working days lost to sickness within the Department for Work and Pensions in each of the last 10 years is recorded in the following table.</p><br /> <br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Period</p></td><td><p>Working Days Lost to Sickness Absence</p></td><td><p>Average Working Days Lost per Employee</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>527,961</p></td><td><p>6.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>620,122</p></td><td><p>6.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>699,731</p></td><td><p>7.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>671,412</p></td><td><p>7.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>846,168</p></td><td><p>8.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>911,809</p></td><td><p>8.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008/09</p></td><td><p>849,448</p></td><td><p>8.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007/08</p></td><td><p>1,053,768</p></td><td><p>10.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006/07</p></td><td><p>1,361,196</p></td><td><p>11.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005</p></td><td><p>1,233,162</p></td><td><p>10.1</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-10-20T14:48:53.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421205/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421205/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421205/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-13","Department for Work and Pensions: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many days were lost to sickness in his Department in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","11773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421206","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-20","<p>The morale of the Department’s staff is not measured although the related concept of Employee Engagement is measured regularly through the Department’s annual People Survey.</p><p>The People Survey is conducted in the Autumn every year and we are currently in the middle of completing this year’s survey.</p><p>Results will be available and made accessible to the public through the Gov.uk website in mid-November.</p><p>Last year’s results can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/397958/dwp-people-survey-2014.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/397958/dwp-people-survey-2014.pdf</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-10-20T13:07:12.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421206/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421206/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421206/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-13","Department for Work and Pensions: Job Satisfaction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent assessment he has made of the morale of his Department's staff.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","11774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421207","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-21","<p>Carer’s Allowance ceases when the claimant earns more than £110 a week. There is not a similar cliff-edge effect in Universal Credit. Carers who combine caring with paid work will continue to have the Carer Element included in the calculation of their overall award for as long as they provide care for at least 35 hours per week for a severely disabled person.</p><p>In Universal Credit, earned income by members of the household is subjected to a work allowance. Different amounts are disregarded from earnings in order to reflect the needs of different types of household and to support the aim that work pays. Carers are entitled to one of these work allowances depending on their family type, although there is not a work allowance specifically for carers.</p><p>Carers who combine work with caring will be able to earn up to their work allowance without their Universal Credit entitlement being affected. If earnings exceed that allowance then the Universal Credit award will reduce gradually as earnings increase.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","11640","2015-10-21T14:04:52.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421207/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421207/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421207/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-13","Carers: Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what effect the introduction of universal credit will have on the income of those working in a job from which they derive net earnings of less than £110 per week and who are the principal carers for elderly relatives with a disability.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","11639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421208","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-21","<p>Carer’s Allowance ceases when the claimant earns more than £110 a week. There is not a similar cliff-edge effect in Universal Credit. Carers who combine caring with paid work will continue to have the Carer Element included in the calculation of their overall award for as long as they provide care for at least 35 hours per week for a severely disabled person.</p><p>In Universal Credit, earned income by members of the household is subjected to a work allowance. Different amounts are disregarded from earnings in order to reflect the needs of different types of household and to support the aim that work pays. Carers are entitled to one of these work allowances depending on their family type, although there is not a work allowance specifically for carers.</p><p>Carers who combine work with caring will be able to earn up to their work allowance without their Universal Credit entitlement being affected. If earnings exceed that allowance then the Universal Credit award will reduce gradually as earnings increase.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","11639","2015-10-21T14:04:52.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421208/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421208/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421208/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-13","Carers: Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what effect the introduction of universal credit will have on the income of those working in a job from which they derive net earnings of at least £111 per week and who are the principal carers for elderly relatives with a disability.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","11640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421209","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-16","<p>A person in full time education will normally not meet the basic conditions for Universal Credit. There are however exceptions to this condition for some people; including people with limited capability for work, those in receipt of Personal Independence Payment, and people with care of dependent children.</p><p><em></em></p><p>There is no entitlement to Carer’s Allowance for people in education 21 hours or more a week because in order to be eligible they would need to be providing care for a severely disabled person for 35 hours a week.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","11642","2015-10-16T12:11:32.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421209/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421209/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421209/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-13","Carers: Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what effect the introduction of universal credit will have on the incomes of those spending more than 21 hours per week in education and who are the principal carers for elderly relatives with a disability.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","11641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421210","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-16","<p>A person in full time education will normally not meet the basic conditions for Universal Credit. There are however exceptions to this condition for some people; including people with limited capability for work, those in receipt of Personal Independence Payment, and people with care of dependent children.</p><p><em></em></p><p>There is no entitlement to Carer’s Allowance for people in education 21 hours or more a week because in order to be eligible they would need to be providing care for a severely disabled person for 35 hours a week.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","11641","2015-10-16T12:11:32.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421210/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421210/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421210/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-13","Carers: Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what effect the introduction of universal credit will have on funding for care available to older people with a disability whose principal carer is engaged in education for no more than 20 hours per week.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","11642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421211","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-20","<p>The level of disaggregation is not readily available. DWP Expenditure for the years 2010-11 to 2014-15 is shown in the table below.</p><br /><p>DWP, Departmental Expenditure Limit Resource Outturn, £million</p><table><tbody><tr><td></td><td><strong>2010-11</strong></td><td><strong>2011-12</strong></td><td><strong>2012-13</strong></td><td><strong>2013-14</strong></td><td><strong>2014-15</strong></td></tr><tr><td><strong>DWP</strong></td><td>9,152</td><td>7,624</td><td>7,497</td><td>7,615</td><td>7,152</td></tr><tr><td>Of which:</td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Health and Safety Executive (net)</strong></td><td>203</td><td>175</td><td>162</td><td>155</td><td>139</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Operational Delivery</strong></td><td>1,294</td><td>2,487</td><td>2,865</td><td>2,866</td><td>2,191</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Employment Programmes</strong></td><td>1,814</td><td>876</td><td>802</td><td>1,037</td><td>950</td></tr></tbody></table><p>More information is available in the Department’s report and accounts which are available at gov.uk. A link to the latest report is provided below:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dwp-annual-report-and-accounts-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dwp-annual-report-and-accounts-2014-to-2015</a></p><br />","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-10-20T15:04:04.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421211/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421211/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-13","Department for Work and Pensions: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to expenditure on (a) DWP Administration, (b) the Government Equalities Office, (c) the