"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420604","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-20","<p>We want a radical reshaping of the relationship between central and local government, ending the merry go round of clawing back local taxes into Whitehall and handing them out again in the form of grants. We will do this by giving local government full retention of its Business Rates by 2020, meaning all income from local taxes will go towards funding local services. We will work closely with the sector over the coming weeks and months to ensure local people have more control over how their money is spent. This will mean looking at the grants that currently go from central government to local authorities, and the range of responsibilities central government asks local government to deliver. There will still be redistribution between councils so that councils don’t lose out just because their area starts from a weaker position. We will set out more detail at the Spending Review.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-10-20T10:07:15.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420604/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420604/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420604/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-12","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he plans to continue paying the homelessness prevention grant to local authorities when the local government grant is phased out.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","11364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420605","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-15","<p>The homelessness prevention grant is part of our £500 million investment in local authority and voluntary sector homelessness services and has contributed to local authorities preventing 935,800 households from becoming homeless since 2010.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-10-15T15:27:26.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420605/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420605/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420605/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-12","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the homelessness prevention grant.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","11365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420606","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-20","<p>The numbers of households categorised by local authorities as being eligible, homeless and in priority need but intentionally so, in each of the financial years since 2004/05, are shown in the first column of the attached table. The numbers of households for whom the immediate outcome of being accepted by their local authority (due to being eligible, unintentionally homeless and in priority need) was to be placed in temporary accommodation, in each of the financial years since 2004/05, are shown in the second column of the table.</p><br />","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","11355","2015-10-20T15:56:02.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420606/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420606/answer","PQ 11356 and 11355.docx","PQ 11356 and 11355.docx","Table - Homelessness/Temporary Accommodation","Table - Homelessness/Temporary Accommodation","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420606/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-12","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many people have been categorised as intentionally homeless in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","11356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420607","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-20","<p>The Government wants to help hard working families achieve their dream of home ownership. The agreement with the National Housing Federation will give 1.3 million housing association tenants the opportunity to purchase their home with Right to Buy discounts.</p><p>The Government will be working closely with the sector on the implementation of the agreement.</p><p>The Right to Buy will be funded through local authorities payments to the Government based on the estimated value of their high value vacant housing, to encourage efficient management of housing assets.</p><p>We will announce more details of the costs of the Right to Buy extension in due course.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-10-20T15:34:00.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420607/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420607/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420607/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-12","Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the likely level of government investment in right to buy schemes in the next five years.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","11354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420608","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-20","<p>The numbers of households categorised by local authorities as being eligible, homeless and in priority need but intentionally so, in each of the financial years since 2004/05, are shown in the first column of the attached table. The numbers of households for whom the immediate outcome of being accepted by their local authority (due to being eligible, unintentionally homeless and in priority need) was to be placed in temporary accommodation, in each of the financial years since 2004/05, are shown in the second column of the table.</p><br />","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","11356","2015-10-20T15:56:01.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420608/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420608/answer","PQ 11356 and 11355.docx","PQ 11356 and 11355.docx","Table - Homelessness/Temporary Accommodation","Table - Homelessness/Temporary Accommodation","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420608/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-12","Temporary Accommodation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many households have been placed in emergency temporary accommodation each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","11355"
