"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420610","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-20","<p>The Government is working closely with the Local Government Association and local authorities already supporting the expanded resettlement scheme to help identify and promote the range of housing options that can be used by local housing authorities to house vulnerable Syrian refugees.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2015-10-20T16:54:56.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420610/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420610/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420610/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-12","Housing: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions his Department has had with local authorities on their capacity to house refugees.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","11272"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420611","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-21","<p>DCMS funds the Portable Antiques Scheme (PAS) at the British Museum through grant in aid. The scheme offers specifically-trained Finds Liason Officers to local Authorities to record Archaeological finds. In order to record finds quickly, these officers support Finders in self-recording, and run training schemes.</p><p>There is a network of 39 Finds Liaison Officers, based in museums and county councils throughout England and Wales and six National Finds Advisers. The data gathered by the Scheme is published on an online database (<a href="http://www.finds.org.uk/" target="_blank">www.finds.org.uk</a>).</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-10-21T11:34:21.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420611/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420611/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420611/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-12","Archaeology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what support his Department provides to finds liaison officers to ensure that detected archaeological finds are properly recorded in a speedier manner in order to encourage more finds to be declared to local authorities.","false","Biography information for Mark Pritchard","The Wrekin","Mark Pritchard","11287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420612","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-20","<p>Under the expanded Vulnerable Persons scheme, local authorities’ costs for the first year of a Syrian refugees resettlement are funded from the Overseas Development Assistance budget. To ensure that local authorities can plan ahead we will also provide additional funding to assist with costs incurred in future years (2 to 5). The Government is working closely with the Local Government Association and individual councils on the details of how funding arrangements for years 2 to 5 will operate.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2015-10-20T16:55:46.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420612/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420612/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420612/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-12","Housing: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what funding the Government plans to allocate to local authorities for housing Syrian refugees; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mark Pritchard","The Wrekin","Mark Pritchard","11283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420613","Home Office","false","2015-11-05","<p>We are working with local authorities to ensure that they are only asked to welcome Syrian refugees that their local structures are able to support. We are talking to them and other partners to ensure that capacity can be identified and the impact on those taking new cases can be managed in a fair and controlled way.</p><p>The Home Office alongside other departments and the Local Government Association will work with individual local authorities who are volunteering to take Syrian refugees. Currently when a referral is made to a Local Authority who has asked to participate in the scheme all relevant information on family make up, age and specific or medical needs is included in that referral so that the Local Authority can make an informed decision to accept or reject the individuals based on the specific needs.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2015-11-05T16:36:48.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420613/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420613/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420613/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-12","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will provide information and data about the housing, health, and social needs of Syrian refugees to enable local authorities to plan for their arrival.","false","Biography information for Mark Pritchard","The Wrekin","Mark Pritchard","11284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420614","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-11-16","<p>This information is not held centrally by the Department.</p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2015-11-16T16:49:55.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420614/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420614/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420614/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-12","Fire Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many firefighters in each fire and rescue authority are qualified trauma technicians.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","11465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420615","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-15","<p>A local planning authority can already require that an infrastructure delivery plan should accompany a planning application if this is specified on a formally adopted ‘local list’ and it is reasonable to expect that the information will be material to the decision.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-10-15T16:22:48.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420615/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420615/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420615/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-12","Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will require builders to submit infrastructure delivery plans prior to main planning applications.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","11432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420616","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-20","<p>The Government recently introduced protection for tenants from unfair eviction where they have made a legitimate complaint about the condition of their home. We have also introduced measures to ensure fairness for landlords, making the eviction process more straightforward in appropriate circumstances such as the persistant non-payment of rent. We believe that the current approach strikes a fair balance between the rights of landlords and tenants and do not have any plans to introduce further restrictions on a landlord’s ability to evict a tenant.</p><p>The Housing and Planning Bill introduced on 13 October contains a range of measures that are intended to crack down on criminal landlords, thereby helping to improve the sector and ensure tenants get a better deal. There will be a blacklist of rogue landlords and letting agents, banning orders for the most prolific and serious offenders, civil penalties of up to £5,000 for certain breaches of housing legislation, Rent Repayment Orders to cover situations where a tenant has been illegally evicted or the landlord has failed to rectify a serious health and safety hazard in the property, and a tougher fit and proper person test for landlords letting out licensed properties, such as Houses in Multiple Occupation.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-10-20T15:35:47.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420616/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420616/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420616/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-12","Private Rented Housing: Evictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to further control the ability of private landlords to evict tenants at short notice.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","11486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420617","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-15","<p>In March 2015, my Department announced that the Jaywick Coastal Community Team would be one of 12 pilots that bring local community, public and private sector delivery partners together to develop an economic plan for their area to help promote jobs and growth in seaside towns. The Jaywick Team is focusing on three key issues:</p><ul><li>Addressing housing and poor infrastructure provision for the existing community</li><li>Supporting the local economy by the location of care and assisted living provision – “Extra Care Village”</li><li>Creating local apprentice and employment opportunities</li></ul><p>My officials meet regularly with Essex County Council and Tendring District Council to discuss the regeneration strategy being prepared for Jaywick.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-10-15T16:21:04.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420617/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420617/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420617/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-12","Housing: Jaywick","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the 30 September 2015 publication, English Indices of Deprivation, what plans his Department has to introduce specific measures to (a) improve the standard of housing, (b) improve the quality of life and (c) liberalise planning rules for house building in Jaywick.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","11444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420618","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-15","<p>Statistics on house building completions by tenure in each local authority district are published in the Department's live tables 253 (annual) and 253a (quarterly), which are available at the following link.</p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-house-building" target="_blank">http://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-house-building</a></p><p>Taken together, house building statistics by housing association and local authority tenures provide estimates of total social housing completions, but these figures understate total affordable supply. This is because the house building figures are categorised by the type of developer rather than the intended final tenure, leading to under recording of affordable housing, and a corresponding over recording of private enterprise figures.</p><p>More comprehensive statistics on affordable housing completions are published in the Department’s live tables 1006, 1006a, 1007 and 1008, which are available at the following link:</p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-affordable-housing-supply" target="_blank">http://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-affordable-housing-supply</a></p><p>These statistics include both newly built housing and acquisitions.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-10-15T16:22:09.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420618/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420618/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420618/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-12","Housing: Lancaster","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many (a) council houses, (b) housing association properties and (c) affordable homes were built in the Lancaster City Council local authority area between (i) 1997 and 2001, (ii) 2001 and 2005, (iii) 2005 and 2010 and (iv) 2010 and 2015.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","11473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420619","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-11-16","<p>The Government’s continued ambition is for greater collaboration between fire and local authorities and between fire, police and ambulance services to deliver a more efficient and effective service for the public. My Department has made available a significant amount of funding to fire and rescue authorities in 2015-16 for this purpose injecting over £65 million to support collaboration projects.</p><p>Our goal is to improve outcomes for the public through closer joint working across all the emergency services, including the NHS ambulance service. My Department in conjunction with the Home office and the Department of Health is currently consulting on the Government's manifesto commitment of enabling closer working between emergency services.</p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2015-11-16T16:51:27.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420619/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420619/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420619/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-12","Emergency Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment the Government has made of the potential for efficiencies from closer working between the ambulance and fire services; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","11494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420620","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-20","<p>How an authority should determine whether or not someone is intentionally homeless is set out in legislation and statutory homelessness guidance, which is available to the public and authorities. It makes clear that housing authorities should consider each case in light of its particular facts and must not adopt general policies which seek to pre-define circumstances that do or do not amount to intentional homelessness. We have no plans to carry out a review.</p><p>Homelessness legislation ensures that families and the most vulnerable always have a roof over their head. This includes cases where households have made themselves homeless and are assessed by a local authority as being in priority need for accommodation. The law places a duty on the authority to secure suitable accommodation for a period that enables the household a reasonable opportunity to secure their own accommodation.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","11545 ; 11579","2015-10-20T15:39:54.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420620/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420620/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420620/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-12","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will conduct a review of local government (a) procedures on and (b) requirements to provide housing to families who become intentionally homeless.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","11495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420621","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-16","<p>We recognise that a range of solutions will be required to reach those in the hardest to reach areas. That is why the Government has invested up to £8 million to support seven pilot projects to explore ways to extend superfast broadband beyond 95% of UK premises, with technologies such as satellite and wireless and using alternative financing models. Decisions on any future intervention will be taken as part of the Spending Review.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-10-16T09:36:57.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420621/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420621/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420621/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-12","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how the final five per cent of superfast broadband coverage will be funded.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","11471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420622","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Government’s consultation on the balance of payments between pay TV platforms and Public Service Broadcasters (PSBs) closed on 30 June 2015. The consultation examined the flow of payments between PSBs and pay TV platforms, and whether regulations relating to these transactions are necessary to ensure broadcasters can deliver the highest quality content, at the best price, to the widest possible audience. The Department for Culture, Media and Sport has received responses, and is now analysing with a view to publishing a Government response in due course.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-10-16T09:38:31.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420622/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420622/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420622/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-12","Television: Royalties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what plans he has for the future regulation of television content royalty payments.","false","Biography information for Nigel Adams","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams","11413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420623","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-21","<p>The decision to transfer of thecost of providing free television licences for over-75s to the BBC was an agreement reached by the Government and the BBC. The Governmentmet both the BBC Executive and the BBC Trust to discuss thison a number of occasions ahead of the announcement.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-10-21T11:38:03.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420623/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420623/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420623/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-12","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions took place between the Government and the BBC on free television licences for people over 75 before the decision was made that the BBC would fund such licences; and when such discussions took place.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","11406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420624","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-21","<p>The over 75’s continue to receive free TV licenses, following agreements between the BBC and Government that the BBC would assume responsibility for the over 75s television licence concession.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-10-21T12:00:12.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420624/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420624/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420624/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-12","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions he has had with age-related third sector or charity organisations on the withdrawal of Government funding for free television licences for people over 75.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","11407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420625","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-27","<p>DCMS funds the Portable Antiques Scheme (PAS), which encouraged the voluntary recording over 100,000 objects in 2014. PAShas an MoU with eBay to monitor any unreported treasures - and calls in the sellers for questioning if illegal sales reported by third parties.PASFinds liasion officers work closely with local police forces when investigating the illegal recovery ofarchaeologicalmaterialfrom the UK. You can find more information on the PAS website -<a href="http://finds.org.uk/" target="_blank">finds.org.uk</a>.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-10-27T15:02:46.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420625/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420625/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420625/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-12","Cultural Heritage: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to prevent illegal online sales of portable antiquities discovered at archaeological sites in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mark Pritchard","The Wrekin","Mark Pritchard","11288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420626","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-19","<p>National Lottery sales are not declining. 2014/2015 was the most successful year for The National Lottery ever, achieving £7.27bn in sales and £1.96bn for good causes. Sales are up on the previous year (£6.73bn) and have even surpassed the record-breaking Olympic year of 2012/2013 (£6.9bn).</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-10-19T14:41:56.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420626/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420626/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420626/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-12","National Lottery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will hold discussions with Camelot on steps they are taking to reverse the recent decline in national lottery sales.","false","Biography information for Mark Pritchard","The Wrekin","Mark Pritchard","11289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420627","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-15","<p>The overall scale and scope of the BBC, including the provision of different genres, is part of the Charter Review discussion. The public consultation looked at these issues and closed on 8 October having received more than 190,000 responses. In the coming months we will continue to listen to the views of the public, industry and this House as proposals for the future of the BBC are developed.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-10-15T09:45:04.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420627/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420627/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420627/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-12","BBC: Religion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether requirements for religious content will be included in the new BBC Charter.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","11308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420628","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-15","<p>I meet regularly with the Football Association, Premier League and Football League to discuss a wide range of issues, including improved access for disabled spectators to Premier League football matches. The Government welcomes the recent announcement by the Premier League for all Premiership clubs to achieve compliance with the <em>Accessible Stadia</em> Guide (which can be found at <a href="http://www.safetyatsportsgrounds.org.uk/sites/default/files/publications/accessible-stadia.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.safetyatsportsgrounds.org.uk/sites/default/files/publications/accessible-stadia.pdf</a> ) by August 2017 and we will be seeking regular updates from the Premier League on progress to implement it.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-10-15T10:37:55.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420628/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420628/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420628/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-12","Football: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will hold discussions with the Football Association about improved access for disabled people to Premier League football matches.","false","Biography information for Mark Pritchard","The Wrekin","Mark Pritchard","11290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420629","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-10-20","<br /><p>The planned out of service date for Tornado GR4 is 2019.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-10-20T14:42:49.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420629/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420629/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420629/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-10-12","Tornado Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, under what circumstances RAF Tornado squadrons will be kept in service after 2017.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","11346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420630","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-10-20","<br /><p>Defence Statistics publish information on a regular basis showing intake figures for the Armed Forces, including the Army and Army Reserve. The most recent information is contained in ‘UK Armed Forces Monthly Service Personnel Statistics September 2015’ and associated tables which is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/uk-armed-forces-monthly-service-personnel-statistics-index" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/uk-armed-forces-monthly-service-personnel-statistics-index</a></p><p>Recruiting targets for the Army Reserve for 2014-15 onwards were defined in the Future Reserve 2020 paper, which was placed in the Library of the House on 19 December 2013, (reference DEP2013-2063) and are still valid. I refer the right hon. Member to the written ministerial statement made by my right hon. Friend the former Secretary of State for Defence the right hon. Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) on 19 December 2013 (Official Report column 121WS). Figures for earlier years may be found in the most recent Quarterly Performance Report which can be found at the following link</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/uk-armed-forces-quarterly-personnel-report-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/uk-armed-forces-quarterly-personnel-report-2015</a></p><p>Official statistics for Regular recruitment targets which may be meanfully compared to the official intake statistics are not produced.</p><p>A summary of regular Army intake for the period in question is as follows, Army Reserve intake is shown from 2012-13 onwards as due to a lack of validated figures prior to 2012 it is not possible to include figures before that period, recruitment targets were not set until October 2013 following the publication of the Reserves White paper:</p><table><tbody><tr><td rowspan="3"><p>Army Reserve</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>2012-13</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>2013-14</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>2014-15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Target</p></td><td><p>Actual</p></td><td><p>Target</p></td><td><p>Actual</p></td><td><p>Target</p></td><td><p>Actual</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>3960</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>2960</p></td><td><p>4900</p></td><td><p>5210</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><table><tbody><tr><td rowspan="3"><p>Regular Army</p></td><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Actual</p></td><td><p>Actual</p></td><td><p>Actual</p></td><td><p>Actual</p></td><td><p>Actual</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>8760</p></td><td><p>11190</p></td><td><p>10300</p></td><td><p>7020</p></td><td><p>8160</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>All totals have been rounded to the nearest 10. Those numbers ending in ‘5’ have been rounded to the nearest multiple of 20 in order to avoid systematic bias.</p><br />","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2015-10-20T14:51:37.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420630/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420630/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420630/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-10-12","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the (a) target and (b) outturn was for (i) regular Army and (ii) Army Reserve recruitment in financial years 2010-11 to 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","11383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420631","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-10-20","<br /><br /><p>The demand plan is an internal note setting out the Army's intake requirement for the Recruitment Partnership Programme contract for the forthcoming year, as required by the contract. It includes commercially sensitive information. Ministry of Defence officials are currently considering whether a redacted version of the plan can be placed in the Library of the House.</p><br /><br />","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-10-20T14:40:30.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420631/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420631/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420631/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-10-12","Army","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will place in the Library a copy of the 2015-16 Army Demand Plan.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","11384"
