"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419811","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-19","<p>The UK wide Statement of Principles is on GOV.UK. At an adjournment debate last month I proposed a roundtable on online retail delivery charges. This is being planned for December. The statement of principles will be discussed at the meeting.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-10-19T13:57:27.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419811/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419811/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419811/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-09","Electronic Commerce","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps the Government is taking to promote its statement of principles for online retailers.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","11152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419812","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-19","<p>None, the Government published the UK wide Statement of Principles on Gov.UK. These endorse the principles drawn up by Citizens Advice Scotland, Citizens Advice and the General Consumer Council for Northern Ireland. The statement of principles has been promoted by those organisations to both retailers and consumers and a copy placed on their websites.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-10-19T13:58:46.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419812/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419812/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419812/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-09","Electronic Commerce","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much the Government has spent on promoting its statement of principles for online retailers.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","11153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419813","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-14","<p>The Government has consulted on the proposal for an income contingent loan of up to £10,000 for Postgraduate Taught Master’s students.</p><p>We are analysing responses to the consultation and expect to publish a response in the autumn.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-10-14T16:18:51.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419813/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419813/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419813/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-09","Postgraduate Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to the proposal in paragraph 1.154 of the Autumn Statement 2014 to introduce income contingent loans for postgraduate taught Master's students, what progress the Government has made on introducing that policy.","false","Biography information for Stephen McPartland","Stevenage","Stephen McPartland","11205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419814","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-14","<p>Since 1st November 2014, the British Business Bank (BBB) has been an operationally independent public limited company, which is wholly owned by Her Majesty’s Government. The tables (attached) highlight BBB programmes by sector for Mid Worcestershire, Worcestershire and the UK. Start-Up Loans are presented separately for breakdowns beyond region.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-10-14T16:12:56.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419814/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419814/answer","Tables for PQ 11200 (21941).docx","Tables for PQ 11200 (21941).docx","BBB Programmes","BBB Programmes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419814/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-09","British Business Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, which 10 sectors received most support from the British Business Bank in (a) Mid Worcestershire constituency, (b) Worcestershire and (c) the UK since that bank was established.","false","Biography information for Nigel Huddleston","Mid Worcestershire","Nigel Huddleston","11200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419815","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-14","<p>Since 1st November 2014, the British Business Bank has been an operationally independent public limited company, which is wholly owned by Her Majesty’s Government. Between November 2014 and August 2015, the British Business Bank have facilitated over £1.56m of lending to 40 businesses in Mid Worcestershire.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-10-14T16:17:34.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419815/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419815/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419815/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-09","British Business Bank: Mid Worcestershire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much support the British Business Bank has provided to small and medium-sized enterprises in Mid Worcestershire constituency since its creation.","false","Biography information for Nigel Huddleston","Mid Worcestershire","Nigel Huddleston","11201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419816","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-14","<p>I refer the hon Member to my answer to question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-07-09/6380/" target="_blank">6380</a></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-10-14T16:20:24.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419816/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419816/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419816/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-09","Students: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect of the abolition of the university maintenance grant on student numbers.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","11237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419817","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-15","<p>The paper referred to provides interim research results on potential pregnancy and maternity-related discrimination and disadvantage in the workplace. The research commissioned in 2014 by Government was jointly managed and funded by the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills and the Equalities and Human Rights Commission, supported by the Government Equalities Office. This is the largest ever study of pregnancy and maternity-related discrimination conducted in Great Britain. Interim findings were published in July 2015 and can be found at: <a href="http://www.equalityhumanrights.com/publication/pregnancy-and-maternity-related-discrimination-and-disadvantage-first-findings-surveys-employers-and-0" target="_blank">http://www.equalityhumanrights.com/publication/pregnancy-and-maternity-related-discrimination-and-disadvantage-first-findings-surveys-employers-and-0</a>.</p><p>The final results, due to be published later this year, will inform the Government’s response.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-10-15T14:20:52.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419817/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419817/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419817/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-09","Flexible Working: Parents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of evidence from research on the extent to which working parents may wish to work more flexibly, but are deterred from making a formal flexible working request for fear of negative consequences; and what steps he plans to take to improve take-up of the right to request flexible working.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","11218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419818","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-19","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that the UK observes its obligations under the WTO Agreements. The UK’s laws and practices on designations of origin for products produced in Israeli settlements are compatible with those obligations.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-10-19T15:52:47.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419818/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419818/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419818/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-09","Origin Marking: Israel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the compatibility of the labelling of goods produced in Israeli settlements with World Trade Organisation law.","false","Biography information for Mark Pritchard","The Wrekin","Mark Pritchard","11227"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419819","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-19","<p>Licensing data shows 67 licences were granted to Saudi Arabia.</p><br /><p>Please note that data from licensing decisions made between 1 April and 30 June 2015 is scheduled to be published as Official Statistics at 9.30am on Tuesday 20 October 2015; and data from licensing decisions made between 1 July and 30 September 2015 is scheduled to be published as Official Statistics at 9.30am on 19 January 2016.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-10-19T14:18:13.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419819/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419819/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419819/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-09","Arms Trade: Saudi Arabia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 1 July 2015 to Question 3711, how many arms export licences the Government has granted to Saudi Arabia subsequent to the information provided in that Answer; and what items were so licensed.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","11231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419820","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-15","<p>The Government takes its export responsibilities very seriously and aims to operate one of the most robust export control regimes in the world. We rigorously examine every application on a case-by-case basis against all of the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria, which includes; ensuing exports are consistent with the UK’s obligations under the United Nations arms trade treaty.</p><p>We undertake appropriate checks using both open and other sources when considering licence applications. To ensure a comprehensive and consistent approach, this will involve Desk and Post in the Foreign and Commonwealth Office and relevant experts from other Departments.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-10-15T15:46:20.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419820/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419820/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419820/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-09","Arms Trade: Yemen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to ensure that arms exports from the UN to Yemen are not being used in breach of export control policy and provisions of the Arms Trade Treaty.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","11263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419821","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-10-14","<p>We are setting up the OGA to have a strong role in the decommissioning of oil and gas infrastructure in the UK Continental Shelf. OGA are developing a decommissioning strategy, working closely with industry and government, to reduce the costs and increase the efficiency of decommissioning, and to encourage technology development. OGA is seeking to develop a more competitive model for decommissioning which stimulates market solutions and innovation. Decommissioning represents opportunities for UK industry to compete for business and I would encourage companies to engage to give themselves the best chance of winning contracts.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-10-14T15:27:02.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419821/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419821/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419821/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-10-09","Offshore Industry: Decommissioning","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what recent assessment she has made of the potential role of ports on Teesside in the decommissioning of offshore oil installations.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","11258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419822","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-14","<p>My Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills and Ministers regularly meet stakeholders from across the Higher Education sector to inform policy development including on Higher Education student support.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-10-14T16:14:09.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419822/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419822/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419822/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-09","Students: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he has had with student body organisations on the effects of removing student maintenance grants.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","11271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419823","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-20","<p>The Government believes in fair wages for fair work and opportunity for all. When an intern meets the legal definition of a worker they must be paid at least the National Minimum Wage. We actively promote fair and open access to paid internships through the BIS-funded Graduate Talent Pool, and our Social Mobility Business Compact and Common Best Practice Code for High Quality Internships ask employers to ensure that any internships they offer are advertised openly and transparently and are paid fairly. We have also made it simpler to name and shame employers that do not comply with national minimum wage regulations and, in addition, complaints from interns are now fast-tracked by HMRC.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","11018 ; 11168","2015-10-20T09:33:29.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419823/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419823/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419823/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-09","Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps the Government has taken in response to the recommendation in the Social Mobility and Child Poverty Commission's report, State of the Nation 2014: Social Mobility and Child Poverty in Great Britain, published in October 2014, that unpaid internships should be eliminated by 2020.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","11169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419824","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-20","<p>The Government believes in fair wages for fair work and opportunity for all. When an intern meets the legal definition of a worker they must be paid at least the National Minimum Wage. We actively promote fair and open access to paid internships through the BIS-funded Graduate Talent Pool, and our Social Mobility Business Compact and Common Best Practice Code for High Quality Internships ask employers to ensure that any internships they offer are advertised openly and transparently and are paid fairly. We have also made it simpler to name and shame employers that do not comply with national minimum wage regulations and, in addition, complaints from interns are now fast-tracked by HMRC.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","11018 ; 11169","2015-10-20T09:33:28.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419824/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419824/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419824/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-09","Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps the Government (a) has taken and (b) plans to take in response to the finding in the Institute for Public Policy Research's report, Why Interns Need a Fair Wage, published in July 2010, that the system of unpaid internships excludes young people who come from less well-off families and ensures that certain industries and professions continue to be dominated from particular backgrounds, perpetuating inequality and dampening opportunities for social mobility.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","11168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419825","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-14","<p>The terms of the Access to Work Assessment Contracts include a specific clause to address the issue of actual or potential conflicts of interest during and after the contract period. The Department ensures that all terms and obligations of its contracts are complied with through an on-going process of commercial and performance management.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-10-14T15:16:03.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419825/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419825/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419825/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-09","Capita: Conflict of Interests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the potential for conflict of interest between Capita's role in carrying out Access to Work assessments while providing interpreting support for British Sign Language users undergoing those assessments.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","11195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419826","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-15","<p>The cost of administering a check off service, and therefore any charge agreed between the trade unions and the employer, varies across the public sector, depending on the legacy payroll systems in place.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-10-15T13:50:13.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419826/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419826/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419826/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-09","Trade Unions: Subscriptions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the contribution by the hon. Member for Croydon South on 14 September 2015, Official Report, column 787, what assessment has been made of the income received by public sector employers from the deduction of trades union dues at source.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","10997"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419827","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-19","<p>This is a matter for individual government departments, to which check-off arrangements are delegated.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-10-19T15:21:14.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419827/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419827/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419827/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-09","Civil Servants: Trade Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the number of civil servants who have the right to deductions at source of trade unions dues in their contract of employment.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","11035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419828","Department of Health","false","2015-10-19","<p>The Government has no current plans to extend smokefree legislation to outside public areas.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-10-19T14:46:56.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419828/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419828/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419828/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-09","Government Departments: Smoking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will consult on implementing no smoking zones outside government buildings for people employed in those buildings.","false","Biography information for Mark Pritchard","The Wrekin","Mark Pritchard","10979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419829","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-14","<p>Individual Electoral Registration (IER) is essential in making the system of electoral registration more secure and less vulnerable to fraud. 96% of electors in Great Britain have already transferred to the new IER registers. As the Electoral Commission has said, many of these retained entries are likely to be redundant, for example where electors have moved home. The latest figures on electors retained from registers before IER, broken down to local authority and regional level, are available online:</p><p><a href="http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/__data/assets/excel_doc/0007/190465/IER-May-2015-electoral-registers-data.xlsx" target="_blank">http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/__data/assets/excel_doc/0007/190465/IER-May-2015-electoral-registers-data.xlsx</a></p><p>They show that the number of carry forwards had declined by two thirds between summer 2014 and May 2015. These figures do not take into account of the work of the annual canvass, which is currently underway, or extra Government funding available to Local Authorities to target remaining carry forward electors specifically. We expect the number of carry forward entries to decline further as a result.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2015-10-14T15:33:00.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419829/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419829/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419829/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-09","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will publish an updated electoral register, including each (a) local authority and (b) parliamentary constituency, with the number of carry-forward electors who have not yet registered under individual electoral registration.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","10863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419830","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-14","<p>The Government has not issued guidance to electoral returning officers on the release of electoral registration statistics in response to Freedom of Information requests.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2015-10-14T15:32:44.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419830/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419830/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419830/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-09","Electoral Register: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what guidance his Department has issued to electoral returning officers on the release of electoral registration statistics in response to Freedom of Information requests.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","10864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419831","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-26","<p>The government regularly publishes information on the job titles and pay grades of senior civil servants along with the numbers of staff they manage and the budgets they are responsible for.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","10866","2015-10-26T15:54:23.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419831/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419831/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419831/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419831/answer/previousversion/23450","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-09","Government Departments: Extended Ministerial Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2015 to Question 8466, if he will list the names, job titles and pay grades of all appointments to extended ministerial offices that have been made to date.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","10865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419832","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-26","<p>The government regularly publishes information on the job titles and pay grades of senior civil servants along with the numbers of staff they manage and the budgets they are responsible for.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","10865","2015-10-26T15:54:23.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419832/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419832/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419832/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419832/answer/previousversion/23451","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-09","Government Departments: Extended Ministerial Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2015 to Question 8466, how many appointments to extended ministerial offices (a) have been made to date, (b) required approval by the Civil Service Commission, (c) are currently under consideration by the Civil Service Commission and (d) have been rejected by the Civil Service Commission.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","10866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419833","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-21","<p>Companies House received the following number of complaints about the possible failure to register the opening of a UK establishment of an overseas company, which is a breach of the Overseas Regulations 2009, for each year since 2010. Companies House will act upon the receipt of a public complaint about a possible failure to comply with the Overseas Companies Regulations 2009 (&quot;the Regulations&quot;). It will carry out an initial investigation and then, if it considers that an offence may have been committed, it will refer the case to BIS solicitors to consider whether a prosecution is justified under the Code for Crown Prosecutors. The principal aim is to achieve compliance with the Regulations; therefore, prosecution action is considered a last resort.</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of Complaints</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010 (from 1 October</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>36</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>26</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015 (to date)</p></td><td><p>8</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-10-21T15:15:40.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419833/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419833/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419833/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-09","Overseas Companies Regulations 2009","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 10 September 2015 to Question 8192, how many public complaints were made about failures to comply with the Overseas Companies Regulations 2009 in each year since they came in to force.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","10867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419834","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-20","<p>The Government recognises and supports the cultural and historical significance of all languages spoken within the United Kingdom, and as a demonstration of its support for Scottish Gaelic, is providing the broadcaster MG ALBA with funding of £1 million in the previous and current financial years.</p><p>Given the current low levels of demand for such a service, providing official responses to correspondence in Scottish Gaelic would represent a disproportionate cost. Therefore, we have no plans to introduce a Gaelic language policy for written correspondence.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2015-10-20T13:39:17.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419834/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419834/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419834/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-09","Government Departments: Scots Gaelic Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, for what reasons the Government does not respond to correspondence written in Scottish Gaelic with a reply in Scottish Gaelic.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","10755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419835","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-19","<p>It is for the independent Commission on Freedom of Information to determine the scope of its review in accordance with its Terms of Reference.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","10763","2015-10-19T11:03:14.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419835/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419835/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419835/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-09","Commission on Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, for what reasons consideration of extension of the scope of the Freedom of Information Act to private contractors has not been explicitly included within the scope of the Independent Commission on Freedom of Information's review.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","10762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419836","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-19","<p>It is for the independent Commission on Freedom of Information to determine the scope of its review in accordance with its Terms of Reference.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","10762","2015-10-19T11:03:14.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419836/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419836/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419836/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-09","Commission on Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will instruct the Independent Commission on Freedom of Information to consider the impact the Freedom of Information Act has had on standards of governance.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","10763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419837","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-19","<p>The costs incurred by the independent Commission on Freedom of Information will be accounted for on publication of the Commission’s report.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-10-19T11:02:13.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419837/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419837/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419837/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-09","Commission on Freedom of Information: Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much he expects the Independent Commission on Freedom of Information to cost the public purse.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","10764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419838","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-19","<p>Ministers appointed the members of the independent Commission on Freedom of Information on the basis of their experience and expertise, and to provide a cross-party balance.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-10-19T11:01:10.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419838/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419838/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419838/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-09","Commission on Freedom of Information: Membership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what criteria was used for deciding the membership of the Independent Commission on Freedom of Information.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","10765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419839","Department of Health","false","2015-10-15","<p>Clinicians are encouraged and manufacturers are mandated to report deaths and other incidents to the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA) if they suspect a device fault.</p><p>The numbers of United Kingdom deaths reported annually since 2010 to the MHRA involving patients implanted with approved pacemakers, are as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Deaths reported involving pacemaker patients</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015 - present</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>According to registry data from 2014, over 35,000 pacemakers are implanted annually in the UK. Therefore the number of reported patient deaths listed above which could have potentially related to pacemaker failure represents no more than 0.01% of this population.</p><p>Analysis of MHRA investigation conclusions revealed that none of the above deaths resulted from a faulty pacemaker.</p><p><strong></strong></p><p>As the UK regulatory authority, the MHRA is responsible for monitoring the safety of medical devices once they have been approved for market. Although the majority of pacemakers are well functioning, the MHRA actively monitor the performance of implants using a variety of methods.</p><p>One key element involves the investigation of device-related adverse incidents, where manufacturers’ mandatory reports are supplemented by voluntary reports from clinicians and members of the public using the yellow card system.</p><p>The MHRA challenges manufacturers if it is believed that the proposed post-investigation action is inadequate to protect public health.</p><p>Every new incident, including those involving pacemakers, is assessed and assigned to an appropriate type of investigation according to its severity and the likelihood of obtaining further information on the cause of the event. All reports, even those unsuitable for further investigation, are fully recorded and subject to periodic trend analysis by the MHRA to look for signals suggesting any possible device-related problems.</p><p>In addition to scrutinizing manufacturers’ device data provided in incident investigations, and their published product performance reports, the MHRA also monitors relevant published research and articles on potential safety concerns as part of its surveillance of the medical device market. If evidence emerges that affects the safety of UK pacemaker patients, the Agency issues advice to the health service and takes any necessary regulatory action.</p><p>Furthermore the Agency actively engages with the clinicians and professional bodies to gauge their opinion on early indications for failure and problems encountered with device usage.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-10-15T14:35:40.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419839/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419839/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419839/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-09","Heart Pacemakers: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many deaths there have been as a result of faulty heart pacemakers in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","10744"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419840","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-19","<p>Electoral Registration Officers (EROs) are currently conducting the first full canvass of households under Individual Electoral Registration (IER). This will help to identify new attainers with Household Enquiry Forms specifically asking for the names of all residents who are over the age of 16.</p><p>The Government has funded youth organisations, including Active Citizens FE, Bite the Ballot and UK Youth, for activities that engage attainers and young people in the democratic process. Cabinet Office has also developed free resources, including Rock Enrol!, for use in schools, colleges and youth groups to encourage people to participate in democracy and register to vote.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2015-10-19T12:07:20.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419840/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419840/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419840/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-09","Electoral Register: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps the Government is taking to confirm and add attainers and young voters to the electoral register before December 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Graham Allen","Nottingham North","Mr Graham Allen","10680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419841","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-19","<p>The most recent report by the Electoral Commission (November 2012) on completeness and accuracy of the register in Northern Ireland showed that 51% of 18 - 19 year olds were registered to vote compared to 76% in Great Britain. The Government has no current plans to extend the Northern Ireland Schools Initiative to the rest of the United Kingdom.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","10714","2015-10-19T12:08:23.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419841/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419841/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419841/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-09","Electoral Register: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will extend the successful Schools Initiative in Northern Ireland established to increase voter registration among 16 to 18 year olds to other parts of the UK before the next 2015 deadline for electoral registration.","false","Biography information for Mr Graham Allen","Nottingham North","Mr Graham Allen","10713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419842","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-19","<p>The most recent report by the Electoral Commission (November 2012) on completeness and accuracy of the register in Northern Ireland showed that 51% of 18 - 19 year olds were registered to vote compared to 76% in Great Britain. The Government has no current plans to extend the Northern Ireland Schools Initiative to the rest of the United Kingdom.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","10713","2015-10-19T12:08:23.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419842/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419842/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419842/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-09","Electoral Register: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment his Department has made of lessons learned from the successful Schools Initiative in Northern Ireland established to increase voter registration among attainers and young voters.","false","Biography information for Mr Graham Allen","Nottingham North","Mr Graham Allen","10714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419843","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-19","<p>The latest information on the figures you have requested can be found in the April 2015 Child and Working Tax Credits published statistics, found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/child-and-working-tax-credits-statistics-provisional-awards-geographical-analyses-december-2013" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/child-and-working-tax-credits-statistics-provisional-awards-geographical-analyses-december-2013</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-10-19T15:26:27.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419843/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419843/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419843/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Welfare Tax Credits: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people are in receipt of tax credits in (a) Glasgow Central constituency, (b) the city of Glasgow and (c) Scotland.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","10756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419844","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-19","<p>HM Revenue and Customs does not routinely publish estimates of VAT revenue accruing to the Exchequer which derives from businesses.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-10-19T15:31:24.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419844/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419844/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419844/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will estimate the proportion of VAT revenue accruing to the Exchequer which derives from businesses with an annual turnover under (a) £150,000 and (b) £250,000.","false","Biography information for Ben Howlett","Bath","Ben Howlett","10778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419845","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-19","<p>The UK has chosen to maintain a high VAT registration threshold, and it is currently the highest in the EU (at £82,000 from 1 April 2015). We believe that the UK’s current registration threshold achieves a reasonable balance between competing interests and reduces the administrative burden on the smallest businesses.</p><p>The Government may not increase this threshold further, aside from maintaining its value in line with inflation, without the consent of the European Commission and the unanimous agreement of all EU Member States.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-10-19T15:32:16.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419845/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419845/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419845/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will review the level of existing VAT thresholds for small businesses.","false","Biography information for Ben Howlett","Bath","Ben Howlett","10779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419846","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-19","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials meet with a wide range of organisations as part of the usual policy making process.</p><br /><p>It might be useful to know that the Treasury publishes a list of ministerial meetings with external organisations. This is available online at: www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/minister_hospitality.htm.</p><br /><p>As you are aware, the FCA is an independent non-governmental body responsible for regulating and supervising the financial services industry. Although the Treasury sets the legal framework for the regulation of financial services, it has strictly limited powers in relation to the FCA. In particular, the Treasury has no general power of direction over the FCA and cannot intervene in individual cases.</p><br /><p>The independence of the FCA is vital to the role it provides as a safety net for consumers with complaints against financial services firms. Their credibility, authority and value to consumers would be undermined if it were possible for the Government to intervene in their decision-making.</p><br /><p>The FCA regularly publishes information on the progress of the redress scheme. This can be found here: www.fca.org.uk/consumers/financial-services-products/banking/interest-rate-hedging-products.</p><br /><p>You may be aware that the Treasury Select Committee’s report into SME lending, published on 10 March, recommended that the FCA collect the information necessary to establish whether there are systemic failures in the redress scheme. The FCA has responded and the Committee, which published this response on 12 October 2015. It can be found here: www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-committees/treasury/Responses/Financial-Conduct-Authority-response-to-Conduct-and-Competition-in-SME.pdf</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","10922 ; 10923","2015-10-19T14:38:34.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419846/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419846/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419846/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Interest Rate Swap Transactions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the Financial Conduct Authority in dealing with complaints relating to the misselling of interest rate swaps.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","10921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419847","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-19","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials meet with a wide range of organisations as part of the usual policy making process.</p><br /><p>It might be useful to know that the Treasury publishes a list of ministerial meetings with external organisations. This is available online at: www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/minister_hospitality.htm.</p><br /><p>As you are aware, the FCA is an independent non-governmental body responsible for regulating and supervising the financial services industry. Although the Treasury sets the legal framework for the regulation of financial services, it has strictly limited powers in relation to the FCA. In particular, the Treasury has no general power of direction over the FCA and cannot intervene in individual cases.</p><br /><p>The independence of the FCA is vital to the role it provides as a safety net for consumers with complaints against financial services firms. Their credibility, authority and value to consumers would be undermined if it were possible for the Government to intervene in their decision-making.</p><br /><p>The FCA regularly publishes information on the progress of the redress scheme. This can be found here: www.fca.org.uk/consumers/financial-services-products/banking/interest-rate-hedging-products.</p><br /><p>You may be aware that the Treasury Select Committee’s report into SME lending, published on 10 March, recommended that the FCA collect the information necessary to establish whether there are systemic failures in the redress scheme. The FCA has responded and the Committee, which published this response on 12 October 2015. It can be found here: www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-committees/treasury/Responses/Financial-Conduct-Authority-response-to-Conduct-and-Competition-in-SME.pdf</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","10921 ; 10923","2015-10-19T14:38:35.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419847/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419847/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419847/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Interest Rate Swap Transactions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent discussions he has had with the Financial Conduct Authority on the misselling of interest rate swaps.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","10922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419848","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-21","<p>HMRC estimates that, on average, businesses moving from the flat rate scheme to standard VAT accounting incur extra administrative costs of £45 per year.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-10-21T13:30:18.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419848/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419848/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Small Businesses: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on SMEs of a move from the flat rate scheme for VAT to the general rate.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","10891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419849","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-20","<p>No such assessment has been made. The Government has chosen to maintain the highest VAT registration threshold in the EU. EU law allows us to increase the threshold in line with inflation, and it has therefore increased to £82,000 with effect from 1 April 2015.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-10-20T16:36:42.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419849/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419849/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419849/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Tourism: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential benefits of increasing the turnover threshold at which it becomes necessary to adopt the general rate for VAT for the tourism industry.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","10892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419850","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-19","<p>HM Revenue and Customs plans to send a notification letter to Scottish taxpayers in December of this year, informing them of the introduction of the new Scottish Rate of Income Tax. As the Scottish Government is yet to set a date for the announcement of its intended rate, it is not possible to state whether the letters will be sent before or after the rate has been announced.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","10833","2015-10-19T15:22:34.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419850/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419850/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419850/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Income Tax: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when HM Revenue and Customs will send a notification letter to Scottish taxpayers to inform them of the introduction of the new Scottish rate of income tax.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","10830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419851","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-19","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) have been liaising with employers and payroll software developers for the last eighteen months to raise their awareness of the Scottish Rate of Income Tax. This has been undertaken through numerous workshops, presentations and publications.HMRC have already published:</p><br /><ul><li>a technical pack (in Dec 2014) outlining the Specified Electronic Submission files for outgoing messages (P6/P9) for 2016/17 <br></li><li>technical specifications for the Specified Electronic Submission for incoming files (FPS/EPS), as well as guidance &amp; test data (June 2015)<p>In addition, test services for the 2016/17 tax year went live on 8 October 2015, enabling payroll developers to submit their test files to HMRC.</p><p>HMRC have also included details of the Scottish Rate in their Employer Bulletin publication, which will assist employers in dealing with queries from their employees, and published guidance on GOV.UK.</li></ul>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-10-19T15:29:48.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419851/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419851/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419851/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Income Tax: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will send detailed information to employers and payroll agents affected by the introduction of the new Scottish rate of income tax to enable them to implement systems and deal with enquiries.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","10831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419852","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-19","<p>People will pay the Scottish Rate of Income Tax if their main place of residence is in Scotland for most of the year. For the vast majority of taxpayers, even those who work remotely or on a mobile basis, this will be a straight forward test of the location of the home they return to when work has finished. HM Revenue and Customs will publish detailed guidance to help people understand how the rules apply to them.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-10-19T15:30:42.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419852/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419852/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419852/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Income Tax: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment HM Revenue and Customs has made of the effect of the new Scottish rate of income tax on remote and mobile workers who are Scottish taxpayers.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","10832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419853","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-19","<p>HM Revenue and Customs plans to send a notification letter to Scottish taxpayers in December of this year, informing them of the introduction of the new Scottish Rate of Income Tax. As the Scottish Government is yet to set a date for the announcement of its intended rate, it is not possible to state whether the letters will be sent before or after the rate has been announced.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","10830","2015-10-19T15:22:34.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419853/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419853/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419853/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Income Tax: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether HM Revenue and Customs intends to send out a notification letter to Scottish taxpayers to inform them of the introduction of the new Scottish rate of income tax prior to or after the rate being set by the Scottish Government.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","10833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419854","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-19","<p>The London Stock Exchange Group and the Shanghai Stock Exchange will carry out a feasibility study on a stock market connection, and will determine the terms of reference in due course.</p><br />","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-10-19T15:21:25.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419854/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419854/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419854/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Stock Market: China","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the terms of reference are for his Department's feasibility study into future connections between UK and Chinese stock markets.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","10835"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419855","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-19","<p>The direct fiscal impact of the policy was set out in Table 2.1 of the Budget document, accessible via the following link:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/443232/50325_Summer_Budget_15_Web_Accessible.pdf</p><br /><p>This figure does not take into account the dynamic economic impacts of the policy. In 2013, the Government published a report modelling the economic impact of the corporation tax cuts announced in the previous parliament. This showed that, through increases to investment and demand for labour, which in turn raise wages and consumption, the cost of corporation tax cuts falls by between 45 per cent and 60 per cent in the long term.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-10-19T15:41:32.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419855/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419855/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419855/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Public Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of the effect of the reduction in the rate of corporation tax on public sector net borrowing and debt.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","10836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419856","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-19","<p>As announced on 16 September, more than 20,000 Pension Wise appointments have taken place, and the website has received over 1.5 million visits.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-10-19T15:15:12.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419856/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419856/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419856/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Pension Wise","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people have booked free guidance sessions with Pension Wise on defined contribution pensions schemes since April 2015; and how many such sessions Pension Wise is forecast to run by the end of the current financial year.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","10807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419857","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-19","<p>a) At Budget 2014, the Government announced it will allow those with a defined contribution pension to draw down from it after age 55 from April 2015, subject to their marginal rate of income tax.</p><br /><p>At Summer Budget 2015, the Government announced a cut in pensions tax relief for high earners by introducing a tapered annual allowance for those with incomes (including the value of pension contributions) of over £150,000.</p><br /><p>The Budget policy costings documents set out the assumptions and methodologies underlying costings for tax policy decisions.</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/295067/PU1638_policy_costings_bud_2014_with_correction_slip.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/295067/PU1638_policy_costings_bud_2014_with_correction_slip.pdf</a></p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/443195/Policy_costings_summer_budget_2015.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/443195/Policy_costings_summer_budget_2015.pdf</a></p><br /><p>All costings in these documents have been scrutinised and certified by the Office of Budget Responsibility (OBR). This is in line with the Memorandum of Understanding between the OBR, HM Treasury and HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC).</p><br /><p>b) The National Audit Office audits HMRC’s financial statements, the adequacy of its revenue collection systems and the value for money it achieved from its spending. This is published as part of HMRC’s 2014-15 annual report: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/hmrc-annual-report-and-accounts-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/hmrc-annual-report-and-accounts-2014-to-2015</a></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-10-19T15:37:07.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419857/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419857/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419857/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the (a) Office for Budget Responsibility and (b) National Audit Office have been given access to the internal HM Revenue and Customs modelling which underpinned the analysis of the economic and fiscal impact of the reforms to defined contribution pension schemes in the July 2014 and July 2015 budget statements.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","10808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419858","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-19","<p>HM Revenue and Customs has collated data on its enforcement actions involving modern slavery since February 2015.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-10-19T15:11:23.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419858/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419858/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419858/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will collect data on the number of enforcement actions undertaken by HM Revenue and Customs involving victims of modern slavery.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","10809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419859","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-19","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials meet with a wide range of organisations as part of the usual policy making process.</p><br /><p>It might be useful to know that the Treasury publishes a list of ministerial meetings with external organisations. This is available online at: www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/minister_hospitality.htm.</p><br /><p>As you are aware, the FCA is an independent non-governmental body responsible for regulating and supervising the financial services industry. Although the Treasury sets the legal framework for the regulation of financial services, it has strictly limited powers in relation to the FCA. In particular, the Treasury has no general power of direction over the FCA and cannot intervene in individual cases.</p><br /><p>The independence of the FCA is vital to the role it provides as a safety net for consumers with complaints against financial services firms. Their credibility, authority and value to consumers would be undermined if it were possible for the Government to intervene in their decision-making.</p><br /><p>The FCA regularly publishes information on the progress of the redress scheme. This can be found here: www.fca.org.uk/consumers/financial-services-products/banking/interest-rate-hedging-products.</p><br /><p>You may be aware that the Treasury Select Committee’s report into SME lending, published on 10 March, recommended that the FCA collect the information necessary to establish whether there are systemic failures in the redress scheme. The FCA has responded and the Committee, which published this response on 12 October 2015. It can be found here: www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-committees/treasury/Responses/Financial-Conduct-Authority-response-to-Conduct-and-Competition-in-SME.pdf</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","10921 ; 10922","2015-10-19T14:38:35.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419859/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419859/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419859/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Serious Fraud Office","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent discussions his Department has had with the Serious Fraud Office on allegations relating to (a) systematic undervaluing of properties owned by small businesses and (b) misselling of interest rate swaps.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","10923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419860","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-19","<p>The government is currently finalising the administration arrangements for the rapid response grant scheme which will open for applications this financial year. The scheme will cover the VAT costs incurred in the purchasing and fitting out of medical emergency rapid response vehicles by charities which are not already in scope of existing VAT refund schemes or are not already funded for VAT. The total grant available across the UK will be £100,000 in 2015-16.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-10-19T11:29:31.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419860/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419860/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419860/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Ambulance Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps the Government is taking to establish a grant scheme to support charities providing rapid response vehicles for medical purposes.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","11040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419861","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-19","<p>HM Revenue and Customs do not have an electronic application portal for applicants for child and working tax credits. New claims for tax credits can be submitted by post or over the telephone.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-10-19T15:27:12.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419861/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419861/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419861/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many reports he has received in each of the last two financial years of HM Revenue and Customs' electronic application portal failing to record and register data and supporting documentation submitted by applicants for child and working tax credits.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","11016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419862","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-29","<p>The Parliament, and its then Treasury Select Committee, dissolved shortly after this report was published and HM Treasury was not able to prepare a response before dissolution.</p><br /><p>HM Treasury is considering the Committee’s recommendations and will be responding to the new Committee in due course.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","10920","2015-10-29T15:16:54.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419862/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419862/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419862/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Small Businesses: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he plans to respond to the recommendations of the Treasury Committee's report, Conduct and competition in SME lending, published on 16 March 2015.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","11212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419863","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-19","<p>The latest information on the number of tax credit recipients under 25 in the UK can be found in table 3.1 of the April 2015 Personal Tax Credits published statistics, found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-tax-credits-provisional-statistics-2013-to-2009" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-tax-credits-provisional-statistics-2013-to-2009</a></p><br /><p>These statistics are published in April and December each year.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-10-19T15:25:37.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419863/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419863/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419863/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Welfare Tax Credits: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people under 25 years old in (a) Glasgow South West constituency, (b) Scotland and (c) the UK receive tax credits.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","11032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419864","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-14","<p>(a) HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) does not enforce non-payment of child maintenance. This is the responsibility for the Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) Child Maintenance Group.</p><p>(b) HMRC does not hold the numbers of fraudulent tax claims submitted to the Child Support Agency. The responsibility for providing HMRC with this information would be for DWP.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-10-14T16:02:04.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419864/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419864/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419864/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many investigations HM Revenue and Customs has carried out for (a) non-payment of child maintenance and (b) allegations of fraudulent tax claims submitted to the Child Support Agency in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","11111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419865","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-19","<p>The Government is making changes to Child Tax Credits which will help put welfare spending on a more sustainable path. The Government wants to move from a low wage, high tax, high welfare society to a higher wage, lower tax, lower welfare society.</p><br /><p>The changes will ensure that work will always pay more than a life on benefits, support will be focused more on those on the very lowest incomes and the system will be fairer upon those who pay for it, as well as those who benefit from it. Taking the welfare changes in the Summer Budget together with the record increases in the income tax personal allowance and the introduction of the New Living Wage, 8 out of 10 working households will be better off by 2017/18.</p><br /><p>The Summer Budget publication also sets out illustrative examples (Table 1.8, p.40) of the combined impact of the changes to welfare, the personal allowance and the National Living Wage on individual households.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-10-19T13:00:00Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419865/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419865/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419865/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Child Tax Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 1.44 of the Summer Budget 2015, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effects of changes to child tax credits on the incidence of (a) in-work poverty and (b) homelessness.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","11157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419866","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-19","<p>The Chancellor’s announcement on 21 September 2015 set out that the government and the Hinkley Point C project company had agreed the terms of a £2 billion guarantee through the UK Guarantees Scheme. This guarantee is the first tranche of debt guarantees that was approved as part of the European Commission’s approval of the wider support package for Hinkley Point C. The government is satisfied that the guarantee remains within the terms set out by the EU Commission.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-10-19T15:08:36.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419866/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419866/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419866/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Loan Guarantee Scheme: China","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the loan guarantee facility offered to Chinese nuclear companies in his announcement in Beijing on 21 September 2015 remains within the scope of the European Commission's state aid decision of 8 October 2014 concerning the Hinkley Point C project; and when the Government informed the Commission of that new loan guarantee.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","11185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419867","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-19","<p>At present the Government has no plans to introduce new taxes on food and drinks.</p><br /><p>The Government is using a range of approaches to promote health outcomes, including working with the food and drink industry to encourage the reformulation of products. A comprehensive ‘childhood obesity strategy’ will be launched later this year.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-10-19T15:19:18.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419867/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419867/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419867/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Taxation: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what his policy is on the introduction of a tax on food with a high sugar content; and what assessment his Department has made of the effect of food taxes on improving dietary choices.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","11151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419868","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-19","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery.</p><br /><p>Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis and are available at:</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel</a></p><br />","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-10-19T15:10:37.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419868/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419868/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419868/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","Treasury: Pressure Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what meetings his Department has had with representatives of (a) the Taxpayers' Alliance, (b) the Confederation of British Industry, (c) the Institute of Economic Affairs, (d) the Adam Smith Institute, (e) the Freedom Association, (f) the Politics and Economic Research Trust and (g) the Midlands Industrial Council in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","11074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419869","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-19","<p>HM Treasury will soon consult on what planning powers will be given to the National Infrastructure Commission, and on its remit.</p><br /><p>It will initially focus on areas of UK government competence. Where spending is devolved, it will be a matter for the devolved governments whether they wish to work with the Commission and how to respond to any recommendations it makes.</p><br /><p>The Commission will provide objective analysis and an independent view on infrastructure needs, but Government will retain the final say on policy and which projects receive government support in being delivered.</p><p><br></p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-10-19T15:09:46.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419869/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419869/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419869/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-09","National Infrastructure Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what planning powers he plans to provide to the National Infrastructure Commission; and what the relationship is between the remit of that Commission and the powers exercised by the (a) devolved administrations and (b) Secretaries of State for (i) Transport, (ii) Energy and Climate Change and (iii) Communities and Local Government.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","11187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419870","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-10-16","<p>Insurance companies determine the flood risk element of the premiums they charge. Insurers use a variety of models to identify flood risk which may differ by area and organisation and will depend on their approach to risk and their underwriting strategies. Insurance companies do not have to disclose the criteria they use. The criteria and data suppliers that insurers use is commercially sensitive information which, if made public, could serve to distort the effective operation of the market.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-10-16T12:34:30.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419870/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419870/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419870/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-10-09","Floods: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will take steps to recommend that insurance companies make public their geographical data suppliers in respect of areas deemed to be at risk of flooding.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","11127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419871","Department of Health","false","2015-10-19","<p>Funding decisions for 2016/17 onwards, including for social care, are subject to the ongoing Spending Review which will review expenditure and future demand for services. This includes considerations such as the forthcoming implementation of the National Living Wage. The Spending Review will be published on 25 November 2015.</p><br />","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-10-19T13:48:00.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419871/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419871/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419871/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-09","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he plans to take to ensure councils have adequate funding to protect social care following the implementation of the National Living Wage in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","11061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419873","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-19","<p>The statutory Homelessness Code of Guidance for Local Authorities includes advice and guidance to authorities on the actions they can take to prevent homelessness where a person is at risk of eviction from a property. This includes negotiation with landlords or with help to address rent arrears for example. It also explains how authorities should carry out their homelessness duties where eviction takes place.</p><p>We have also introduced protections for tenants against “retaliatory eviction”. Where a tenant makes a genuine complaint about the condition of their property that has not been addressed by their landlord, their complaint has been verified by a local authority inspection, and the local authority has served either an improvement notice or a notice of emergency remedial action, a landlord cannot evict that tenant for 6 months using the ‘no-fault’ eviction procedure (a section 21 eviction). A ‘no fault’ eviction is one where the tenant does not have to have done anything wrong, for example not paying the rent, to be asked to leave. The landlord is also required to ensure that the repairs are completed. These rules, set out in the Deregulation Act 2015, apply to all new assured shorthold tenancies that start on or after 1 October 2015. A guidance note is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/465275/Retaliatory_Eviction_Guidance_Note.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/465275/Retaliatory_Eviction_Guidance_Note.pdf</a></p><br />","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-10-19T13:24:53.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419873/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419873/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419873/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-09","Private Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what advice his Department issues to local authorities on advising private rented sector tenants subject to court orders for possession on the steps they should take to find accommodation.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","11229"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419874","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-20","<p>Devolving the power to extend Sunday trading hours will enable local areas to determine the Sunday trading hours that best reflect the need of local people. There are many reasons why people will continue to choose small retailers. They offer a diverse range of products and services from convenient locations. This is perhaps why the convenience sector last year saw the opening of two new stores a day and growth in turnover of 5%.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-10-20T15:35:59.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419874/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419874/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419874/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-09","Sunday Trading","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the potential economic effect on small businesses of changing Sunday trading laws.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","11118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419875","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-19","<p>The Government is committed to a secure future for refuge provision, as set out in our Manifesto, and is determined to ensure that no victim is turned away from the support they need. At Budget the Chancellor announced an additional £3.2 million to increase specialist accommodation support for victims, including refuges, and provide more help for victims to access that support. This is in addition to the £10 million announced in 2014 to enable local authorities to strengthen refuge services. Our significant investment shows our clear commitment to maintaining and boosting refuge provision. Future funding arrangements are a matter for the Spending Review.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","11020","2015-10-19T14:19:15.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419875/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419875/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419875/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-09","Refuges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to ensure that women's refuges have a sustainable source of funding after the current funding arrangements end on 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","11129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419876","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-16","<p>No assessment has been made. Housing Benefit is not designed to provide support for homelessness funding – that is a matter for the Department for Communities and Local Government and the devolved Governments in Scotland and Wales.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-10-16T12:36:30.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419876/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419876/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419876/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-09","Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to paragraph 2.110 of the Summer Budget 2015, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of limiting backdating in housing benefit to four weeks on homelessness provision reliant on funding from that benefit.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","11159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419877","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-14","<p>Assured shorthold tenancies give landlords the automatic right to possession at the end of the initial fixed term on giving the tenant two months' notice. Possession through the courts can also be sought before the end of the initial fixed period, where the tenant has broken certain terms of the tenancy, such as by not paying the rent.</p><p>We have made it easier for landlords to evict a tenant where it would be legitimate to do so, by introducing a prescribed form of notice which will reduce errors and remove the need for a landlord to specify the exact date a tenancy comes to an end, while retaining the requirement to give two months’ notice. The legislation came into effect on 1 October 2015 and we have published guidance and the required forms are at: <strong><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/465275/Retaliatory_Eviction_Guidance_Note.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/465275/Retaliatory_Eviction_Guidance_Note.pdf</a></strong></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-10-14T15:13:00.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419877/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419877/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419877/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-09","Private Rented Housing: Evictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to support private landlords in evicting tenants who are in breach of contract.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","11194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419878","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-19","<p>The Government is committed to preventing youth homelessness and we are taking specific action across England to support young homeless people into stable accommodation, education training or employment.</p><p>We have invested £14 million to enable Crisis to support 10,000 vulnerable single people into privately rented tenancies, of which 41 projects are specifically targeted at young people.</p><p>Our £15 million Fair Chance Fund payment by results scheme is supporting 1,600 vulnerable homeless 18-25 year olds into accommodation, education training and employment. Projects for the scheme are being delivered across the country including North East areas such as Newcastle, Northumberland, South Tyneside, North Tyneside, Gateshead, Durham and Sunderland.</p><p>In addition, the Government is investing £40 million in Platform for Life, a lower rent shared accommodation programme to provide young homeless people a stable base for work and study. We have also implemented the ‘Youth Accommodation Pathway’, good practice model that supports young people to remain in the family home where it is safe to do so and offers tailored support for those who cannot. This has been disseminated across all English local authorities.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-10-19T17:03:26.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419878/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419878/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419878/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-09","Homelessness: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to improve supported accommodation for homeless young people in (a) Easington constituency, (b) County Durham, (c) the North East and (d) England.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","11029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419879","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-13","<p>To further support new housing supply and home ownership we are announcing further changes to permitted development rights. When the Government brought forward measures from the summer 2014 ‘Technical consultation on planning’ we undertook to further consider the case for extending the office to residential reforms, which are helping to provide more new homes on brownfield land. These rights are being used, with almost 4,900 applications received by councils in the five quarters ending June 2015 and 4,000 approved during the same period, without needing to go through the whole planning process.</p><p>Given the extensive use of the right, I can confirm that the Government intends to make permanent the permitted development right that provides for offices to change to residential use and extend the right to allow for demolition of the office and replacement by new housing on a like for like basis. This has the potential to allow for a new building to better accommodate new homes and improve design quality. We will allow for those applicants who already have prior approval or who secure a new prior approval to have three years from the date of their approval in which to complete the change of use.</p><p>Those areas that are currently exempt from the office to residential permitted development right, such as the City of London, the London Central Activities Zone and Central Manchester will remain so until May 2019. This will provide time for local authorities with exemptions to bring forward an Article 4 direction in line with national policy for these areas if they wish. Alongside this, we will also bring forward new permitted development rights for three years that allow buildings up to 500m2 used for light industry compatible with housing, to change to residential use. There will also be a permanent right for launderettes of up to 150m2 to change to residential. These changes will further increase the contribution to housing delivery and reduce unnecessary planning regulations.</p><p>These permitted development rights allow more development to take place without the need for a planning application. They will be subject to prior approval, allowing consideration by the local planning authority of specific planning matters.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-10-13T15:03:08.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419879/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419879/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419879/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-09","Change of Use","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of the merits of (a) extending and (b) making permanent permitted development rights to convert offices to residential buildings.","false","Biography information for Mike Freer","Finchley and Golders Green","Mike Freer","11024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419880","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-19","<p>The Government is looking at the full costs and benefits of devolution proposals in line with Government guidance. This is supported by detailed conversations with areas to help them refine their work such as guidance about onward devolution to neighbourhoods.</p><p>The Government fully supports local authorities applying the concept of social value more widely than required by the Public Services (Social Value) Act 2012 and this is reflected in the Revised Best Value Statutory Guidance which was published in March of this year and can be viewed at the link below:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/revised-best-value-statutory-guidance</p><p><br></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-10-19T13:17:30.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419880/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419880/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419880/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-09","Local Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with local government representatives on ensuring social value is taken into account in proposals for greater devolution; and what his policy is on the recommendation of the Local Government Association's National Procurement Strategy for Local Government on the wider adoption of Public Services (Social Value) Act 2012.","false","Biography information for Chris White","Warwick and Leamington","Chris White","11210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419881","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-19","<p>DCLG has an on-going dialogue with a range of partners. For example DCLG consulted travelling showpeople on recent changes to planning policy.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-10-19T16:47:42.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419881/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419881/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419881/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-09","Travellers: Entertainers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to foster links with travelling showpeople.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","11043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419882","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Department of Energy and Climate Change has requested local authorities in England to annually measure, and report on their websites, greenhouse gas emissions data for their own estate and operations. A collation of the data extracted from local authority websites for the years 2008/09 to 2012/13 can be found on gov.uk:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/sharing-information-on-greenhouse-gas-emissions-from-local-authority-own-estate-and-operations-previously-ni-185#summary-of-local-authorities-ghg-emissions-data-for-20112012-and-20122013" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/sharing-information-on-greenhouse-gas-emissions-from-local-authority-own-estate-and-operations-previously-ni-185#summary-of-local-authorities-ghg-emissions-data-for-20112012-and-20122013</a>.</p><p>From 2013/14 DECC ceased to collate and publish the data on gov.uk.</p><p><strong><br> <br> </strong></p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-10-16T13:40:06.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419882/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419882/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419882/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-10-09","Local Government: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what data her Department holds on the carbon footprint and emissions of local authorities.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","11055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419883","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-19","<p>Details of Ministers' and Permanent Secretaries meetings with external organisations are published up to 31 March 2015 and can be accessed on Gov.uk at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ministers-transparency-publications" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ministers-transparency-publications</a></p><p>Further publications of Ministerial and Permanent Secretaries meetings will be published in due course.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-10-19T16:49:48.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419883/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419883/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419883/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-09","Department for Communities and Local Government: Pressure Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what meetings his Department has had with representatives of (a) the Taxpayers' Alliance, (b) the Confederation of British Industry, (c) the Institute of Economic Affairs, (d) the Adam Smith Institute, (e) the Freedom Association, (f) the Politics and Economic Research Trust and (g) the Midlands Industrial Council in the last 12 calendar months.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","10994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419884","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-19","<p>The Government is committed to a secure future for refuge provision, as set out in our Manifesto, and is determined to ensure that no victim is turned away from the support they need. At Budget the Chancellor announced an additional £3.2 million to increase specialist accommodation support for victims, including refuges, and provide more help for victims to access that support. This is in addition to the £10 million announced in 2014 to enable local authorities to strengthen refuge services. Our significant investment shows our clear commitment to maintaining and boosting refuge provision. Future funding arrangements are a matter for the Spending Review.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","11129","2015-10-19T14:19:15.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419884/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419884/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419884/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-09","Refuges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he plans to take to ensure that women's refuges (a) have a sustainable source of funding and (b) continue to enable women to move between local authority areas after 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","11020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419885","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-19","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government collects data on the numbers of households accepted as owed a homelessness duty, where the reason the household is in priority need is that the applicant is aged 16 or 17 years old. There have been no such cases in County Durham in the last 12 months.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-10-19T17:00:57.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419885/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419885/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419885/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-09","Homelessness: Durham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many 16 and 17 year olds were presented as homeless to Durham County Council in the most recent 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","11004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419886","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-19","<p>Since the Lancashire Enterprise Zone was established in 2012 the Local Enterprise Partnership and UK Trade and Investment have actively promoted the Enterprise Zone as a good place for companies to set up or expand their businesses.</p><p>Two companies have also set up on the Enterprise Zone’s other site at Warton, already attracting 25 jobs.</p><p>Work has recently started on BAE’s training facility on the Enterprise Zone site in Samlesbury. This is a part of BAE’s national commitment to double the number of apprentices they train bringing important opportunities and skills to the area. The new facility is expected to be completed by September 2016.</p><p>An announcement about the Blackpool Airport site will be made in due course.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2015-10-19T16:47:07.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419886/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419886/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419886/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-09","Enterprise Zones: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what progress has been made in developing enterprise zones at (a) Blackpool Airport and (b) Warton.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","10824"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419887","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-19","<p>This is not a matter for the Department for Communities and Local Government.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2015-10-19T16:49:20.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419887/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419887/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419887/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-09","Air Displays: Shoreham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will consider issuing guidance restricting the taking of photos and videos following the Shoreham air show crash.","false","Biography information for Ben Howlett","Bath","Ben Howlett","10840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419888","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-20","<p>The numbers of households with children accepted as homeless in each of the Boroughs of the Liverpool City region in the financial years 2004/05 to 2014/15 are shown in the attached table.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-10-20T16:18:54.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419888/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419888/answer","PQ 10853.xlsx","PQ 10853.xlsx","Table","Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419888/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419888/answer/previousversion/23411","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-09","Homelessness: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many children have been registered as homeless in each borough in the Liverpool City Region in each of the last five financial years.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","10853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419889","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-20","<p>Figures for the numbers of children transferred to temporary accommodation are not collected centrally. The numbers of children in temporary accommodation on the last day of the financial years 2004/05 to 2014/15 in each of the Boroughs of the Liverpool City region are shown in the attached table.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-10-20T16:16:49.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419889/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419889/answer","PQ 10854.xlsx","PQ 10854.xlsx","Table","Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419889/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419889/answer/previousversion/23412","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-09","Temporary Accomodation: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many children in each borough in the Liverpool City Region have been transferred to temporary accommodation in each of the last five financial years.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","10854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419890","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-11-16","<p>Local people expect their local authorities to make the most of its land and assets, sharing their estate with other organisations and selling empty or high value property that is unnecessarily being retained. To ensure local people are able to scrutinise how their local authority manages its assets the Government made it a legal requirement for local authorities to annually publish details of the land and assets it owns in a readable format.</p><p>Under the Local Government Transparency Code 2015, local authorities are required to publish details about the land it owns (subject to a few exceptions), including details of its location, and the value of its social housing stock.</p><p>Local authorities were required to first publish details of its land and assets by February 2015 and details of their social housing stock by September 2015.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-11-16T16:49:10.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419890/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419890/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419890/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419890/answer/previousversion/23363","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-09","Local Government: Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what obligation there is on local authorities to publish online a property asset register; and to what timetable such an obligation must be met.","false","Biography information for John Howell","Henley","John Howell","10871"
